<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     06-12 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Claim Victories as 10th Rainy Season Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist guerrillas fighting in
Cambodia said in a broadcast available Sunday that they killed or
wounded nearly 3,000 Vietnamese soldiers during May.
   The claim contradicted earlier pronouncements by Hanoi, which
said fighting had died down and it could therefore begin
withdrawing troops.
   The clandestine Khmer Rouge radio said 2,821 Vietnamese soldiers
had been killed or wounded during the first month of the 10th rainy
season of the war. It said Hanoi's administrative networks had been
dismantled in 537 villages, 11 communes and one township.
   Past rainy seasons have usually favored the guerrillas, who are
fighting the mechanized, conventional forces Vietnam has maintained
in Cambodia since its late 1978 invasion.
   ``They lack both fighting forces and food supplies, and their
aggressor soldiers are increasingly demoralized,'' said the
broadcast, made available in Bangkok. ``In sum, the Vietnamese have
failed and are a complete impasse.''
   Vietnam, however, has announced that a greatly improved security
situation in Cambodia would allow it to pull 50,000 troops out of
Cambodia over the next seven months. The partial withdrawal may
begin late this month.
   Western analysts, who are generally skeptical of Khmer Rouge
claims, say there has been a sharp drop in fighting in Cambodia in
recent months. They speculated that the Khmer Rouge and other
guerrilla groups may be stockpiling weapons and positioning
themselves for a big push when Hanoi's forces are scaled down.
   The Khmer Rouge, ousted from power by the Vietnamese, are allied
to two non-communist groups in a loose coalition.
</TEXT>
