<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Begins Over Islamic State Religion Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS byline, LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with strike
beginning, CORRECTS thruout that law already in effect, PICKS UP
graf 7 pvs ```They have'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of a law that made Islam the
state religion closed stores and halted traffic in the capital
Sunday as they began an eight-hour nationwide strike.
   However, the monsoon rain kept police and protesters out of the
streets of Dhaka.
   The country's mainstream opposition called the strike to condemn
the law passed Tuesday by the 300-seat Parliament and signed into
law by President Hussain Muhammad Ershad.
   Foes of the law had led torchlight parades through Dhaka on
Saturday.
   The government tightened security in the capital and other
cities in preparation for the strike Sunday. Riot police in trucks
followed several small protest parades Saturday evening, but did
not interfere.
   Among those who called the eight-hour general strike are three
major opposition political alliances.
   At least 30 people have been injured and 35 vehicles damaged in
repeated clashes with police since Parliament approved the bill.
   ``We have several thousand police on constant duty in Dhaka and
elsewhere. We are going to deploy more for tomorrow,'' a Home
Ministry source told The Associated Press on Saturday, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Ershad attacked those organizing the strike.
   ``They have called this hartal (strike) against Allah, his
prophet and his religion,'' Ershad told Moslems at a Dhaka mosque
after Friday prayers.
   He denied charges that the bill was aimed at perpetuating his
rule, which began with a bloodless coup by the former army general
in 1982.
   ``None can rule unless Allah wishes it,'' Ershad said.
   The measure amends the nation's constitution by inserting the
sentence: ``The religion of the republic is Islam, but other
religions may be practiced in peace and harmony.''
   Opponents of the bill, mostly opposition politicians, women,
students and members of the minority Christian, Hindu and Buddhist
religions, say they fear it will lead to imposition of harsh
Islamic rule based on the Koran.
   More than 85 percent of the country's 105 million people are
Moslems. But the government denies it plans to change the nation's
British-based civil law.
</TEXT>
