<HEAD>Iran Official Denies Reports That Khomeini Dying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high Iranian official denied reports
that Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini was terminally ill, Iran's
official news agency said Sunday.
   Iran's Interior Minister Ali-Akbar Mohtashemi was quoted by the
Islamic Republic News Agency as saying he met the national leader
last week. He said the revolutionary patriarch ``is now in perfect
shape'' in the broadcast monitored in Nicosia.
   Khomeini, 87, has been reported to be in frail health since he
suffered a heart attack two years ago. There have also been
unconfirmed reports that he has cancer.
   Mohtashemi called the latest report ``a Zionist scheme to cheer
up Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and his demoralized army.'' Iran
and Iraq have been waging war for nearly eight years.
   The U.S. CBS television network reported Thursday that
intelligence reports indicated that Khomeini ``may now be very
close to death.''
