<2ND_LINE>BC-Korea-Protests,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Battle Riot Police During Funeral March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas to drive back
students who tried to storm the government party's headquarters
Sunday during the funeral of a radical who committed ritual suicide.
   Hundreds of riot police firing volleys of tear gas pushed back
waves of charging students who sought to reach the offices of the
Democratic Justice Party. The screaming students hurled hundreds of
firebombs, and streets were covered with blazing gasoline as
running clashes flared across the center of the city.
   ``Down with the military fascists,'' radical students yelled,
and they hurled rocks and firebombs at police in Seoul's main
shopping district. Protesters destroyed a police truck with
firebombs.
   But riot police quickly pushed protesters back and chased them
through the city for several miles. Radicals hurled rocks at the
Japanese Embassy's information office and smashed windows.
   The fighting broke out during a funeral procession by about
10,000 radical students and sympathizers for Park Rae-chun, who
died Monday after setting fire to himself in an anti-government
protest. It was the third ritual suicide by a radical student since
May 15.
   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent radical student
protests during the past month. Thousands of students trying to
reach North Korea for talks on reuniting the divided Korean
peninsula battled riot police in major street clashes Friday.
   Some marchers shouted ``Yankee go home'' Sunday, but the protest
was less anti-American than others in recent days. Instead, it was
directed mainly at the government of President Roh Tae-woo.
