<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congressman'sCallers Bjt   06-12 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congressman's Callers, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Massive Call-in Campaign Ties Up a Congressman's Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a month, the telephones in the office of
Rep. William J. Hughes, D-N.J., have been tied up by members of an
anti-pornography group who have been urged to phone him and keep
calling ``till you get through.''
   Constituents have been unable to reach Hughes, the House
speaker's staff has had to send a page to contact him and even an
exasperated Hughes has been kept from reaching his secretary when
he's away from the office.
   About 10,000 calls and nearly 20,000 letters have arrived in a
campaign orchestrated by the American Family Association, of
Tupelo, Miss., which told its members that an anti-pornography bill
would die in a subcommittee chaired by Hughes.
   ``Perhaps you believe that a congressional office looks like
Home Shopping Network, with dozens of operators sitting before
computer terminals, ready and able to take messages,'' the
congressman wrote the Rev. Donald E. Wildmon, the group's executive
director, on May 23, complaining about the tactic, and calling it
needless.
   Hughes, chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee on crime,
said the bill is very much alive, and will have a second hearing on
Thursday. Any delays have been caused by the diversion of staffers
from the bill to work on the letters and phone calls, he said.
   Callers to Hughes' office are now greeted by a recorded message
from the seven-term congressman that is on two answering machines.
The machines were paid for by members of Hughes' staff, who decided
the crisis could not wait for House officials to buy the devices.
   After advising callers on other matters to dial another number,
Hughes tells those interested in the pornography bill:
   ``You can be certain that I and the other 200 sponsors of this
important measure will do all we can to see that it becomes law in
a timely fashion.
   ``Thank you for calling. There's no need to leave a message.
Your call is being counted automatically.''
   Hughes said in the interview, and in letters to House colleagues
and Wildmon, that the family association fed its members inaccurate
information, including an allegation that pornographers are
twisting arms of lawmakers to kill the bill.
   But the most inaccurate message, Hughes said, is that the Child
Protection and Obscenity Enforcement Act of 1988 is dying in the
House Judiciary subcommittee on crime.
   ``We're in the hearing process,'' Hughes said. ``Wildmon
demanded we abandon that process and pass the bill with no
amendments.''
   Hughes said that some provisions in the bill raise ``sensitive
First Amendment concerns.''
   Noting the 11-year-old association's letter asks for donations,
Hughes said the money appeal may be the real message the group
wants to convey.
   The legislation encompasses a number of recommendations from the
Reagan administration's Commission on Pornography.
   Some of its provisions would allow government seizure of money
and property derived from violation of pornography and obscenity
laws; use of wiretaps in obscenity investigations; prohibition of
obscenity in cable television programming; and creation of a new
crime of receiving or possessing obscenity with the intent to
transfer.
   Wildmon told his followers in early May that the legislation
``is about to die'' in Hughes' committee, and urged supporters,
``If his phone is busy, keep calling till you get through.''
   The letter said pornographers are ``spending a lot of money,
twisting a lot of arms and pressuring a lot of congressmen,'' and
asked, ``If you can help defray these unexpected costs, I'd be
grateful. You can use the enclosed envelope.''
   Wildmon said in an interview that he regrets the inconvenience
suffered by Hughes' staff, but contended he only wrote the letter
after the crime subcommittee staff refused to tell him about plans
for the bill.
   Hughes replied that he doubted that allegation, since the staff
fields such routine inquiries all the time.
   Asked what evidence he had that the bill would die in committee,
Wildmon said, ``I was told by a number of people who knew what they
were talking about.'' Asked who they were he replied, ``No
comment.'' He also declined to say how he knew pornographers were
pressuring lawmakers.
   Wildmon denied that the purpose of his letter was to raise
money, commenting, ``It cost me $79,000 to send the letter. To
date, we raised $42,000. If I'm going to raise funds by losing
$37,000 I'm going to be out of business in a hurry.
   ``It was a two-page letter and there were three sentences of an
apology, saying I've got expenses to meet.''
   Wildmon said the group had 330,000 supporters, a number based on
the 170,000 ministers and 160,000 others who receive the group's
publications. The American Family Association, Wildmon said, is a
group that ``promotes things that would enhance the family'' and
has taken positions against pornography, abortion, and some
broadcast entertainment shows.
</TEXT>
