<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-88 1212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BaptistConvention Bjt   06-12 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baptist Convention, Bjt,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderates Battling For Southern Baptist Comeback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Baptists squared off Sunday
for another battle over control of the nation's largest Protestant
denomination, now firmly in the hands of the fundamentalist wing.
   As thousands of ``messengers'' gathered here for their annual
convention, some observers said the moderate camp might make a
comeback after nine years of defeat.
   ``It looks as if moderates could win in San Antonio,'' wrote
Daniel M. Allen, editor of the ``SBC Cause,'' urging the other side
to bring in voters to avert such an outcome.
   Convention business begins Tuesday after a day of preliminary
meetings and preaching. Up to 40,000 people are expected to attend
as representatives of the church's 14.7 million members.
   The conflict in the Southern Baptist Convention, as the
denomination is known, has intensified over the last year as
increased fundamentalist power drove various leaders out of office
and imposed tighter rules of belief.
   The struggle, fought largely over the issue of whether the Bible
is the literal truth, has stirred up bitter feelings and sharp
words.
   ``Clever men have stripped us of our rights,'' said John F.
Baugh, a Houston businessman and layman of the moderate camp.
Fundamentalism, he said, brings out an ``insatiable appetite for
power and demand for conformity.''
   ``It's time to stop this nonsense of barbarian attacks on that
which we hold dear.''
   A pro-fundamentalist former convention president, the Rev. James
T. Draper Jr. of Euless, Texas, said after a recent clash with a
moderate leader: ``It seems to be a situation of who can outmuscle
the other. They have given us no alternative.''
   A man in the middle, the Rev. Charles Fuller of Roanoke, Va.,
who for three years has headed a peace committee trying to calm the
turmoil, said the denomination is ``in a crisis of spirit.''
   The peace plan, he said, has been repeatedly violated and there
has been an ``acceleration of political activity'' by both sides
with partisan strategy meetings held in numerous states.
   At the center of the conflict is the denomination's powerful
presidency, which has the authority to appoint trustees who control
Southern Baptist agencies and institutions.
   Most of those boards now have fundamentalist majorities as a
result of the wing's nine years of presidential victories.
   The crucial decision at this week's meeting is election of a new
president. The two camps have rallied behind the expected opposing
nominees, and campaigns for them have rolled across the country.
   Backed by the fundamentalist wing is the Rev. Jerry Vines,
co-pastor of the 18,000-member First Baptist Church of
Jacksonville, Fla.
   The expected moderate nominee is the Rev. Richard Jackson of
Phoenix, Ariz., pastor of the North Phoenix Baptist Church, also
with 18,000 members.
   Both are fundamentalists in their views of the Bible, whose
interpretation has been at the crux of the struggle, but Jackson
doesn't favor imposing his view on institutional trustees, while
Vines does.
   ``I would not appoint anyone to any committee,'' Vines said,
``who did not endorse'' prescriptions laid down by the peace
committee.
   It insists the Bible is without error and on belief in its text
as literal truth _ that Adam and Eve were real people, that the
biblical miracles actually occurred, and that the Bible accurately
records history.
   Jackson said, ``I don't believe there ought to be a control
group,'' and that if he wins election, it would mean ``a change to
allow Baptists to be free again.''
   The winner will succeed the Rev. Adrian Rogers of Memphis,
Tenn., a fundamentalist standard-bearer who has held the post a
customary two years. His previous election in 1979 inaugurated the
fundamentalist tide.
</TEXT>
