<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Strategy     06-12 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Strategy,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supporters Sigh with Relief at New Bush Aggressiveness</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: `Punch' in 13th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid the cheers that greeted George Bush's speech
to a Republican gathering were sighs of relief from party activists
pleased that he finally took the offensive against Democrat Michael
Dukakis.
   While the high command of the Bush presidential election
campaign pushed at the weekend conference for grass-roots work from
GOP regulars, party people from 16 states voiced new hope about the
vice president's prospects.
   Bush himself set last Thursday as an important turning point in
his campaign, using a speech in his adopted hometown of Houston to
lash out at the Dukakis record and the Massachusetts governor's
``out of the mainstream'' beliefs.
   Top Bush campaign aides said it always had been the plan that
Bush would turn his rhetorical guns on Dukakis _ but only at the
end of the primary and caucus season, when the identity of his fall
opponent was unmistakable.
   Bush said he thought Dukakis had ``pretty well shot his specific
bolts'' at him, and said, ``we're just beginning.''
   This proved heartening to Republicans who traveled to Denver for
the first of three unity conferences scheduled by the Republican
National Committee. Two more will be held in Cincinnati and Atlanta.
   ``I wanted to see Bush become his own man as soon as possible
because you've got to grab the initiative,'' said Bill Hughes, a
Bush campaign chairman from Vancouver, Wash. ``I was afraid that
Bush would wait until after the August convention to go and speak
out.''
   Hughes and other Republicans interviewed over the weekend agreed
that Bush still must overcome the obstacle of campaigning for
president while holding the office of vice president. And they said
he must be careful of moving too far away from President Reagan
because that could alienate people in his own party.
   ``I think it was critically important for him to start talking
about the facts about Michael Dukakis,'' said Barbara Campbell,
state GOP chairman in Montana. ``This was something I was really
pleased to see.''
   Several GOP figures said that Bush's early clinching of the
Republican Party nomination _ the late-April Pennsylvania primary
put him over the top _ had the effect of forcing the vice president
to the sidelines. They also said this caused Bush too often to be
on the defensive, to find himself questioned more on the Reagan
administration record than on his own plan for the nation's future.
   ``Our contest didn't last as long. We ended watching the Michael
Dukakis-Jesse Jackson show from the sidelines,'' said New Mexico's
Gov. Garrey Carruthers. ``I think that's cost him.''
   Carruthers said Bush would have to work especially hard in
western states where there was an absence of any genuine GOP
nomination competition late in the primary season.
   Punch Green, Bush's state campaign chairman in Oregon, said the
vice president's wide-ranging attacks on Dukakis' positions and his
record as governor will help ``make the contrast come out.''
   Not only that, he said, Bush seems far more comfortable making
speeches in which he couples explanations of his own positions with
criticisms of those held by Dukakis.
   ``I was just elated'' with Bush's speeches in Houston Thursday
and in Denver Friday, Green said. ``For the first time in a long
time, I heard a real campaign speech from my candidate.''
   Bush and his top campaign aides seemed buoyed by the
tub-thumping speeches of support given at this unity conference by
former GOP White House rivals Bob Dole, Jack Kemp and Alexander M.
Haig Jr.
   But the vice president's aides and the men who likely will be
Bush campaign surrogates also said the Republican ticket must work
hard to retain some of the Democratic and independent support that
Reagan enjoyed in 1980 and 1984.
   Richard Pinsky, who worked on Pat Robertson's campaign, said
that ``tens of thousands'' of Democrats crossed over to the GOP to
support Robertson.
   Pinsky said the party must work hard to keep these
``issue-driven'' voters in the Republican fold.
   Kemp, R-N.Y., said the Bush campaign must not write off any
region of the country or any group.
   And Bush pointedly reached out for Hispanic support, saying he
opposed a proposal to make English the official language and saying
he didn't feel people ought to be threatened by ``the growing
Hispanic-American population.''
   Francisco ``Joe'' Barrego of Denver, executive director of the
GOP's State Nationalities committee, said Bush is ``putting all his
affirmative actions out front.''
   ``I think he's doing the right thing right now,'' said Barrego,
whose organization speaks for people from Cuba, Czechoslovakia,
Latvia, Japan, Chinese and several other countries.
</TEXT>
