<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   06-12 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Killed As Israelis Fight Fires Blamed on Arabs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli bus driver shot and killed an
18-year-old Palestinian on Sunday after his passenger bus was
stoned, a hospital official said. Firefighters battled dozens of
blazes blamed on Arab arsonists.
   The army confirmed the stoning of the bus near the West Bank
town of Jericho and said an Arab man was reported dead. It said it
was investigating the circumstances of his death.
   In Hebron, stone-throwing protests broke out for a third day.
Near Tel Aviv, an Israeli man was seriously injured when he was hit
with a rock.
   A spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Mubarak Awad,
an Arab-American advocate of civil disobedience, would likely be
deported by Monday after losing an appeal to Israel's Supreme Court.
   The court said Awad, who has a home in Wapakoneta, Ohio, did not
have a legal residence permit and was in Israel under an expired
visa in his American passport.
   An army official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said an
Israeli civilian driver fired at assailants who stoned his
passenger bus as he drove past the Ein el-Sultan refugee camp near
Jericho.
   An official at Jericho Hospital said a camp resident, Saed
Mohammed El Hakak, died of wounds to the heart and back after he
was shot by the bus driver. The official spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The death raised to 205 the number of Palestinians killed since
the uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
began Dec. 8. Two Israelis have died.
   Three more fires broke out Sunday, and Police Minister Chaim
Bar-Lev blamed Arab arsonists for brush and forest fires that have
destroyed at least 35,000 acres of trees and pastures since May.
   ``There is no doubt that it is part of the intefadeh (uprising)
and linked to what is happening in the territories and to Israeli
Arabs,'' Bar-Lev told Israel radio.
   The latest fires erupted in the Bar Giora Forest outside
Jerusalem, near an Israeli weather station outside Tel Aviv, and
near the Jerusalem suburb of Ramot. The radio said a Gaza teen-ager
was detained and confessed to setting the weather station fire.
   Bar-Lev said several Arab suspects have been detained, including
two Arab teen-agers who have confessed to setting some of the fires.
   A leaflet published by the underground leadership of the
uprising called on Arabs to ``destroy and burn all the enemies'
agricultural and industrial resources.''
   In Hebron, eight Palestinian teen-agers were treated for effects
of tear gas after a clash with soldiers at Al Hussein High School,
an official at the city's Alia Hospital said.
   The army confirmed there were riots at the high school but had
no further comment.
   Near Tel Aviv, 27-year-old Israeli Shimon Baranes was in a
cardiac intensive care unit at Assaf Harofe Hospital after being
hit by a rock on a road connecting the Tel Aviv suburbs of Nes
Ziona and Rishon Lezion, said police spokeswoman Orit Daka.
   Ms. Daka said police detained several Arab suspects. She
declined to elaborate. But Israeli radio said a 17-year-old
Palestinian confessed to the attack.
   The expulsion order against the Jerusalem-born Awad, 44, a U.S.
citizen, came despite repeated appeals against the move by U.S.
officials. Israeli officials claimed Awad encouraged violence in
the occupied territories.
   ``There is no reason why we shouldn't deport this man who is one
of the leaders of the intefadeh,'' said Shamir spokesman Yossi
Ahimeir. ``He (Awad) claims he is non-violent, but much violence
has resulted from his activities.''
   Awad's American-born wife, Nancy Nye, has denied Israeli charges
that her husband authored leaflets urging violence. But his ideas
for strikes and tax boycotts have been adopted by the uprising's
leaders.
   The government ordered Awad's deportation May 6. Awad appealed
to the Supreme Court, which upheld the government's decision June 5
but gave no specific date for his expulsion.
</TEXT>
