<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wright-Ethics Bjt   06-12 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Ethics, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Speaker Says He's `Confident' He'll Be Cleared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright denied Sunday that he
had violated House conflict-of-interest rules in his financial
dealings and declared ``I am extremely confident'' of being cleared.
   ``I'm haven't done anything dishonest or illegal,'' said the
Texas Democrat. ``I'm convinced I haven't violated any rules of the
House.''
   Wright's comments came during back-to-back appearances on
CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation'' and ABC-TV's ``This Week with David
Brinkley.''
   They were part of his response to an announcement Friday by the
House ethics committee that it was beginning a preliminary inquiry
into the allegations. Wright held a two-hour news conference Friday
to deny the allegations and he repeated many of those statements on
Sunday.
   Wright called the charges ``a partisan political ploy'' raised
by Republicans seeking to deflect Democratic charges of ethical
violations by current and former members of the Reagan
administration.
   ``It's a partisan ploy and it will be revealed to be a partisan
ploy,'' Wright said on the CBS program.
   The committee's inquiry was originally suggested by Rep. Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., but the panel said its investigation would range
beyond the scope proposed by Gingrich.
   Next month, Wright will preside next month over the Democratic
National Convention and he said Sunday that he doesn't expect the
ethics investigation to have any effect on that role.
   Asked on the CBS show if he would give up that chairmanship,
Wright said, ``I don't expect to.''
   Asked if his running the convention would hurt the Democrats,
Wright answered, ``There is no cloud over my head, no sir. ... I've
done nothing unethical, nothing illegal, nothing violative of the
rules of the House.''
   Wright declined to say if he thought the investigation should be
handled by an independent counsel, rather than the ethics committee
in the Democratic-controlled House.
   ``I'm not trying to tell the committee how to conduct its
inquiry,'' Wright said.
   Asked if he wanted the investigation done by the committee or an
independent counsel, Wright answered, ``I don't have a preference.''
   But he continued, ``I want it resolved and I want it resolved as
quickly as possible'' and he pledged full cooperation.
   Wright defended his book, ``Reflections of a Public Man,'' from
which he received a 55 percent royalty totaling about $55,000.
Questions have been raised about whether that royalty percentage is
higher than is normally paid.
   ``There was nothing wrong with the contract,'' Wright said,
later adding, ``I think it's a good book.''
   Asked about reports that his friends were buying the books as a
way to give financial support to Wright, he answered, ``I didn't
sell these books'' to friends.
   ``Royalty proceeds are going to my favorite charity _ Mrs.
Wright and me,'' he said.
   The ethics committee is investigating whether Wright used one of
his staff members to work on the book at taxpayer expense, whether
the royalty amounts were excessive, and whether they were paid in
return for Wright giving some of his campaign business to William
Carlos Moore, the publisher.
   Moore served more than four months in federal prison after
pleading guilty in 1975 to income tax evasion charges. Wright had
written a letter to the federal court on Moore's behalf.
   ``It may have been poor judgment'' to write the letter, said
Wright, although he defended his long friendship with Moore and
said, ``I'm not ashamed of that.''
   ``Sure, I've made mistakes of judgment, but I haven't done
anything dishonest or illegal,'' Wright said.
</TEXT>
