<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Islam     06-12 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Islam,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Calls Strike, Protests Law Making Islam State Religion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police clashed Sunday with
demonstrators protesting a constitutional amendment that made Islam
the state religion. Authorities said 50 people suffered minor
injuries.
   The demonstrations coincided with a one-day strike called to
protest the new law, passed Tuesday by Parliament and signed into
law by President Hussain Muhammad Ershad.
   Police and witnesses said about 20 vehicles, most of them
state-owned buses, were damaged by the demonstrators and that two
bicycle rickshaws were set ablaze. They said 30 people were
arrested.
   Police said there was no major violence and that groups of
protesters were small because of heavy rains.
   Most of the injuries occurred when police with wooden sticks
charged demonstrators outside Dhaka University, near Dhaka College
and at a ferry terminal in nearby Sadarghat, witnesses said.
   The strike, which was called by 20 major opposition parties to
protest the legislation, closed down most shops and private
businesses. Government offices remained open, but attendance was
reported as poor.
   The strike disrupted transportation, including inter-city bus
service, and delayed flights from Dhaka's airport.
   The United News of India news agency said several trains were
stalled when protesters blocked tracks.
   Reports from other cities, including Chittagong in the south and
Sylhet in the north, indicated widespread compliance with the
strike, which ended at dusk.
   Rashed Khan Menon, leader of a five-party leftist opposition
alliance, said the adherence to the strike indicated that ``the
people have rejected the law making Islam the state religion.''
   The opposition parties claim the new law is illegal because it
was passed by a Parliament dominated by Ershad, whose party won a
majority in a 1986 election the opposition contends was rigged. The
20 major opposition parties have no vote in Parliament since they
boycotted elections last March, saying that fair polling could not
be held under Ershad, a former army general who took power in a
bloodless 1982 coup.
;aiting on a Union City street corner for a bus to
New York City, said the presidential campaign has not been
interesting, especially since neither Gov. Thomas H. Kean nor Sen.
Bill Bradley have taken an active role.
   ``They can still be vice president and that would make this a
better election,'' she said.
   On the famed Boardwalk in Atlantic City, tourists seemed to
favor Dukakis, but many stressed that they were ``settling'' only
because they dislike Bush.
   ``He seems as if he's been in the background for the past eight
years, and he hasn't done very much,'' said Ken Stout, who was
taking time out from a Communication Workers of America union
convention.
   ``The only other candidate I might have supported has been
involved in scandals,'' he said. ``I liked Gary Hart _ his
appearance, his charisma.''
   Another Hart fan was found waiting for a train in Newark. Tim
Morin, 21, of Sea Bright, said Hart ``would have made a good
president. I don't care what he does in his private life.''
   Looking realistically at the potential ticket, Morin said he was
satisfied with the Republican and Democratic choices, but ``I like
Dukakis best.''
   Back on the Boardwalk, Stout said the only way Bush could win
``is if he comes up with a strong running mate.''
   Nick Pomponio, a 36-year-old computer technician from Gloucester
Township, said he would like to see Jackson as Dukakis' running
mate.
   ``I think it would be a big boost for minorities,'' he said.
``He (Jackson) seems like he can handle the vice presidential job
and Dukakis seems like he would be a good president.''
   Pedro Rivera disagrees. The Camden resident said he doubts he
will even vote in the general election in November.
   ``I don't think Jesse will be in the running,'' he said.
   Lillian Lazar of Philadelphia looked patriotic dressed in red,
white and blue. But her sentiments over the likely presidential
candidates were largely disappointment.
   ``They're both lousy,'' she said. ``Dukakis is too weak; he's
another Jimmy Carter. And Bush is a big mouth. I don't like his
tactics, and I think he lies. I think he knows more about the
Contra situation but he says he doesn't.''
   Two rare Bush supporters turned up among the Boardwalk's morning
relaxation crowd.
   ``The government now is run by Republicans and it's good so
far,'' said John Ciarlone of Trenton, with his wife, Catherine,
nodding in assent next to him. ``Dukakis is not a strong leader.''
</TEXT>
