<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SiberiaFlight     06-12 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Siberia Flight,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nome Real Estate Agent Is Dauntless Promoter Of Alaska-Siberia
Connections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years ago, James Stimpfle would
stand on the beach in Nome and release balloons to float across the
Bering Strait, hoping to help thaw a Cold War ban on travel between
Alaska and Siberia.
   People laughed and called him crazy.
   But on Monday, Stimpfle will take off on a flight to Siberia,
accompanied by 80 politicians, Eskimos and reporters, crossing a
border that has been closed for 40 years.
   ``There was a lot of skepticism at first,'' Stimpfle recalled
Thursday from Nome, in a telephone interview often interrupted by
calls from the Alaska governor's office and others helping to plan
Monday's ``Friendship Flight'' to the Siberian city of Provideniya.
   ``There were a lot of people who thought it wouldn't happen in
our lifetime,'' Stimpfle said. ``There were a lot of people who
thought I was eccentric and questioned my loyalty and my
motivations.''
   The real estate agent says his motivations are simple: Two years
ago, at the start of Alaska's oil recession, business was slow and
he had time to think up ways of improving his own fortune and that
of Nome, a town of 3,700 people on Alaska's western coast.
   Stimpfle, 40, figured that if someone could pry open the
Alaska-Siberia border, closed in 1948 because of Cold War tensions,
then Nome could become an economic center for both sides of the
Bering Strait.
   He envisioned increased trade, joint economic ventures, and
tourist excursions by airplanes and cruise ships between Nome and
Siberia.
   He also saw opportunities for cultural exhange. His wife,
Bernadette, is a King Island Eskimo, and Stimpfle heard stories of
how Eskimos earlier this century took boats to Siberia to trade and
visit relatives.
   ``I heard tales of people wanting to go over there, and I
wondered why they weren't doing anything about it,'' Stimpfle said.
   He set out to do something.
   In addition to the balloons, he got a huge ``Peace'' sign in
Russian placed on Little Diomede Island, just three miles from the
Soviet island of Big Diomede in the Bering Strait.
   Stimpfle also fired letters off to American and Soviet leaders.
   ``I've probably written somewhere between 500 and 700 letters _
probably 5,000 to 6,000, including copies,'' he said. ``It was the
shotgun approach. I hit them at the very top, I hit them in the
middle, and I hit them at the bottom.''
   Gradually, Siberia fever began to catch on in Nome. Local radio
station KNOM started broadcasting a weekly update on Siberia-Alaska
events in Russian and English, later adding a Russian ``word of the
day.''
   Stimpfle also was aided by good timing: Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's policy of openness paved the way for improved
Alaska-Siberia relations.
   Last August, the Soviets allowed American swimmer Lynn Cox to
cross from Little Diomede to Big Diomede, and Siberian medical
researchers signed a joint research agreement with Alaskan
scientists in November.
   The biggest break came last fall, when Alaska Airlines jumped on
the ``Friendship Flight'' bandwagon, hoping to establish a regular
tourist route, he said. Government officials who brushed off a real
estate agent's letters about flights to Siberia began getting
similar letters from executives of a major corporation.
   ``As long as just one person was doing it, it never would have
reached this level of credibility,'' Stimpfle said.
   Stimpfle would like to see the whole Bering Sea border opened.
He would like to see more joint ventures in fishing,
telecommunications, and trade.
   Many who once scoffed at his dreams now give him the benefit of
the doubt.
   ``It was only a short while ago that this flight was a dream,''
said Lou Cancelmi, Alaska Airlines spokesman. ``I personally
wondered if this day would ever come.
   ``I don't think Jim Stimpfle ever thought for a moment that it
wouldn't, and that's what it takes to make something like this come
true.''
</TEXT>
