<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Violence,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100 Injured In Third Day Of Violence In Northern India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobs stoned police cars and tried to
burn down a police station in Kashmir state Sunday in clashes that
injured 100 people, including 70 lawmen, the United News of India
said.
   A government increase in electricity rates has prompted three
straight days of protests in the northern state, the agency said.
   Thirty policemen were injured when a mob stoned their station
house in the state capital at Srinagar and attempted to burn it
down.
   Police fired warning shots and burst tear gas canisters in
several neighborhoods of the capital to break up crowds, UNI said.
   At one site, youths throwing firebombs set a billboard on fire.
A number of police cars were stoned, UNI said.
   At least 55 people were injured in clashes on Saturday. Three
people were killed in police firing and more than 30 others were
injured on Friday, the first day of violence. Many shops have been
shuttered since Friday.
   UNI said riot police were out on the streets to enforce an order
prohibiting the gathering of more than five people. Paramilitary
forces have been placed on alert, the news agency said.
