<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AIDSMeeting     06-12 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Meeting,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Research Shows Drug Restores IQs of Children With AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS drug can dramatically boost the
intelligence of youngsters whose brains are damaged by the AIDS
virus and even restores their ability to walk and talk, researchers
said Sunday.
   Damage to the brain is one of the earliest and most devastating
of the effects of the lethal virus in children. The research
suggests that the drug AZT can reverse these symptoms and
apparently bring virus-damaged brain cells back to health.
   AZT, also known as zidovudine or Retrovir, is the only medicine
routinely used to suppress the AIDS virus, called HIV. In adults,
it can slow the progression of AIDS but does not cure it.
   The latest research, directed by Dr. Philip A. Pizzo of the U.S.
National Cancer Institute, was presented at the Fourth
International Conference on AIDS.
   Pizzo's findings came unexpectedly during testing of a portable
pump to administer the drug to children. He found that youngsters'
IQ scores increased about 15 points, and many of the other severe
brain symptoms of the virus also went away.
   ``Everybody who looks at this data has to get excited,'' said
Dr. Daniel Hoth of the U.S. National Institute of Allergy and
Infectious Diseases. ``We are all nervous by small numbers (of
patients studied), but the data itself is very exciting.''
   More than 7,000 people, most of them doctors and scientists,
from 138 countries gathered in Stockholm for the opening Sunday of
the fourzoZO-[64|x}zys, there were 25 deaths among patients
who got AZT alone, compared with 11 among people who got both drugs.
   AIDS damages the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
