<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-USPlanes     06-12 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-US Planes,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Bishops Oppose Plan To Accept U.S. Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REGGIO DI CALABRIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishops in southern Italy have
assailed a plan by NATO to transfer 72 U.S. F-16 fighter-bombers
from Spain to Italy.
   Bishops in Puglia and Calabria, the regions where the planes are
likely to be based, issued statements criticizing the government
for agreeing to accept the fighter wing, which Spain no longer
wants.
   Four Calabrian bishops issued a statement late last week which
they described as an ``ethical evaluation'' of the plan. ``Arms,
when they are a power game, are structures of sin,'' their
statement said.
   They said it would be ``ethically irritating'' if the F-16s are
based in Calabria ``as an economic solution to our long-standing
problems.''
   Earlier in the week, seven Puglian bishops said ``Puglia is
already paying a heavy price in servitude to programs of military
armament'' and the region ``could constitute a top priority
target'' if the planes are based there.
   Spain recently said the jets of the 401st Tactical Fighter Wing
must leave Torrejon Air Base outside Madrid. On June 4, the Italian
government agreed to accept the 72 jets subject to parliamentary
approval.
