<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Mississippi     06-12 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Mississippi,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mississippi River Nearing Record Lows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mighty Mississippi could hit record
low levels this summer because of the drought plaguing the Midwest
and northern Plains, and already has fallen enough in places to
ground barges, officials say.
   The river stood at just 8 feet on the Vicksburg gauge on May 28,
the second-lowest reading on record for that date. By Friday, it
had fallen to 3.8 feet, and it was expected to fall to 3 feet by
Monday and continue dropping.
   Monday's predicted reading would be the record low for this time
of year _ about 30 feet below normal. The lowest reading at
Vicksburg for any date was in the early 1930s when the river
dropped to minus 6.7 feet below the level considered as the zero
point.
   At Memphis, Tenn., the river could sink below the 7{-year-old
record of minus 7.3 feet by July 13, according to a 28-day forecast
released by the Lower Mississippi River Forecast Center in Slidell,
La.
   ``The river is still very deep and dangerous, but this is a
record low,'' said Michael Logue, spokesman for the U.S. Army Corps
of Engineers' Vicksburg District.
   In some areas, the river remains deeper than 100 feet, Logue
said. But many points along the boat traffic channel have fallen
below the minimum 9-foot depth needed for normal navigation.
   That means big problems for towboat operators who must lighten
cargoes and run the risk of equipment damage if they run aground.
   Robin Radlein of the National Weather Service River Forecasting
Center in Slidell, La., said it would take heavy rainfall over a
large part of the central United States to raise the river
appreciably. And that's not likely this time of year.
   ``The types of stages we're reporting now are similar to what
you'd normally get in late September, after a hot, dry summer,''
she said. ``And we've still got that ahead of us.''
   Normally, this would be the high water season, Logue said, but
the Vicksburg District expects to have to dredge soon near
Greenville to keep the channel open.
   ``It looks like it's going to be a major challenge this year to
maintain our navigation project,'' Logue said. ``I'm sure the
economic impact is in the millions of dollars already from people
having to carry shallow loads. It has an impact on the whole
central part of the country.''
   Steve Golding, owner of Ole Man River Towing Co. in Vicksburg,
said the drought has cut into his profits.
   Ole Man River is loading barges for a draft of 8.6 feet rather
than the normal 9.6 feet, ``and that last foot sometimes is your
only profit margin,'' Golding said. Current cargoes generally are
about 10 to 15 percent lighter, he said.
   The cost of pushing the load is the same or higher, because
trips take longer, Golding said. Maintenance costs are higher
because of problems with running aground, he said.
   Golding said the navigable channel is so narrow in places that
northbound tows must wait downstream for southbound towboats to
pass.
   Last weekend, 55 barges ran aground at Memphis, closing that
stretch of the river for two days while the tows were disassembled
and moved.
   Friday, the river was reopened from Cairo, Ill., to St. Louis
for the first time in two days after numerous tows ran aground. The
Red River, a Louisiana tributary of the Mississippi, is closed
indefinitely, with some boats stranded upstream.
   ``It makes for an unpredictable trip,'' Golding said. ``And it
puts a lot of stress on the pilots. Last week, we ran aground with
one barge and knocked a hole in the bottom. We also knocked a
rudder off one of our boats.''
</TEXT>
