<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Alabama     06-12 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Alabama,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alabama Charity Concert Draws Estimated 35,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT PAYNE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   June Jams are a thing of the future for
Alabama, says the country band's lead singer Randy Owen.
   The group's seventh annual charity concert Saturday drew 35,000,
and Owen said past problems won't deter the group from keeping the
concert a tradition.
   Saturday's attendance was far below the 61,000 people who showed
up in 1986, when Alabama was at the peak of its popularity. But
last year's June Jam was hit with heavy rain and paid attendance
fell to 20,000, leaving no money for charity.
   The first five June Jams raised $1.5 million.
   Because of last year's problems, Owen and other band members
fought rumors that this year's concert would not occur. Once plans
became final for Saturday's concert, the band members had to dispel
rumors that this would be the last.
   Owen said he is already making plans to mark the state's
homecoming celebration, Alabama Reunion, at June Jam VIII.
Festivities will include having the Alabama Symphony Orchestra join
the band on stage to sing its hit ``My Home's in Alabama.''
   Many entertainers joined Alabama for the daylong concert,
including the Charlie Daniels Band, Exile, K.T. Oslin, Carl
Perkins, the Bellamy Brothers, Sweethearts of the Rodeo, Dan Seals,
Gary Morris and Ricky Van Shelton.
   Fans began lining up for the concert 12 days early. First in
line was Julie Hall, 19, of Bowling Green, Ky. Miss Hall, who has
seen the last four jams, said, ``I sacrifice my social life,
everything, for the two weeks.''
   At the concert site she lived out of her red Ford Escort, which
was packed with clothes, suntan lotion, and a boombox.
</TEXT>
