<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Khomeini Bjt   06-12 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Khomeini, Bjt,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran's Interior Minister Denies Khomeini Is Dying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's interior minister on Sunday denied
a Western news report that Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini is dying of
cancer and said the leader is healthy.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
quoted Ali Akbar Mohtashemi as saying that he met Khomeini several
days ago and that he is ``now in perfect shape.''
   Western analysts believe that a power struggle with Tehran's
fractious hierarchy will intensify as various factions seek to
seize control of the Islamic revolution after the 87-year-old
Khomeini dies.
   Mohtashemi said in an interview in Sunday's edition of the
English-language Tehran Times daily that the foreign media has been
claiming for years that Khomeini's health was failing.
   He charged that the latest report in the United States by the
CBS television network was ``a Zionist scheme to cheer up Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein and his demoralized army.''
   Iran has been at war with Iraq since September 1980.
   CBS said on Thursday that intelligence reports indicated that
Khomeini ``may now be very close to death.'' It quoted the reports
as saying ``the Ayatollah's cancer has spread from his prostate to
his liver'' and that he ``may only have two or three months to
live.''
   Mohtashemi, a hard-liner linked with Shiite Moslem extremists
holding foreign hostages in Lebanon, said the report could be seen
as an Israeli-U.S. response to Khomeini's appointment of Parliament
Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani as acting commander-in-chief of Iran's
armed forces.
   Khomeini named Rafsanjani, one of his closest aides, as military
chief in the wake of two battlefield defeats by Iraq in the nearly
8-year-old gulf war.
   Khomeini has long been reported to be in a frail condition since
he suffered a heart attack two years ago, touching off scores of
reports he was dead or dying.
   He was last seen in public May 13, when he briefly shuffled into
the street outside his heavily guarded home in the north Tehran
suburb of Jamaran to vote in parliamentary elections.
   Khomeini held the post of comander-in-chief under Iran's
revolutionary constitution and had only relinquished it once before
since 1979, when he appointed President Abdolhassan Bani Sadr in
1980. Bani Sadr fled Iran a year later, hounded by radicals who
considered him too liberal.
   Khomeini's apppointment of Rafsanjani rekindled speculation that
the aging patriarch's condition was deteriorating. Khomeini has
appeared fragile and slow-moving in his few recent public
appearances broadcast by Iran's state-run television, also
monitored in Nicosia.
   Speculation that Khomeini was ailing heightened Friday after
IRNA reported that Rafsanjani and President Ali Khamenei had
visited Khomeini's designated successor, Ayatollah Hussein-Ali
Montazeri, in the holy city of Qom, 100 miles south of Tehran, on
Wednesday and Thursday.
   The agency said the men discussed ``various current issues''
with Montazeri. But it did not elaborate or give any indication
that the meetings were linked to Khomeini's health.
   Rafsanjani and Khamenei are rivals in the power struggle under
way within the Tehran hierarchy over who will run the country in
the post-Khomeini era.
   Although Khomeini has designated Montazeri, 65, his successor,
the high-ranking cleric lacks Khomeini's power base.
   He also has been opposed by several leading figures, including
Rafsanjani, long considered the most powerful figure in Iran after
Khomeini.
   When the patriatch appointed Rafsanjani as military leader, he
said he had acted at the urging of Khamenei, chairman of the
Supreme Defense Council.
   But most analysts believe that Khomeini said that to avoid
publicly humiliating Khamenei, whose power has been eroded in
recent months, and deepening the political divisions in Iran.
</TEXT>
