<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Elections     06-12 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Elections,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Launches Ad Campaign Promoting Local Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two days after banning calls
for election boycotts, the government Sunday launched an
advertising campaign to promote participation in municipal
elections scheduled for October.
   Full-page newspaper ads urged South Africans to ``let your vote
speak for you'' in the nationwide elections Oct. 26.
   ``Vote for a better life for yourself and those who are dear to
you,'' said another ad. ``Let the people of South Africa be heard.''
   It will be the first time South Africans of all races go to the
polls on the same day. They will be voting for more than 7,000
seats on municipal councils in their racially segregated
communities.
   Most anti-apartheid organizations in South Africa, as well as
the outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement, oppose
black participation in any elections until the black majority is
granted full political rights at the national level.
   The black ANC movement is fighting the government's policy of
apartheid, which establishes a racially segregated society in which
the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs.
   The government, while describing itself as ``pro-democracy,''
says it will never accept a one-person, one-vote system that would
allow the blacks to overrule the 5 million whites.
   On Friday, when it extended a national state of emergency for a
third year, the government imposed a new regulation outlawing calls
for boycotts of elections, except by a registered political party
competing in an election.
   The far-right Conservative Party, which opposes even limited
concessions to blacks, charged that the $2.3 million ad campaign
constitutes use of taxpayers' money to spread propaganda on behalf
of President P.W. Botha's National Party.
   A confidential outline of the ad campaign, disclosed by a
Conservative Party leader who obtained a copy, said the
government's public credibility was not good. An advertising agency
suggested in the document that animated cartoon characters be used
in television ads to promote voting, because direct communication
from the government might be ``unacceptable to the public.''
   Information Minister Stoffel van der Merwe defended the campaign
last week, saying it was not partisan.
   ``It is pro-democracy and anti-revolutionary, for which we do
not apologize,'' he said.
   The ads published Sunday exhorted voters to ``vote for the
candidate who will best look after your interests.''
   The white municipal elections will provide the Conservative
Party with another chance to gain strength at the expense of the
National Party. The Conservatives won three parliamentary
by-elections earlier this year, and they predict a sweep of local
elections in towns and small cities throughout Transvaal province
in the north, where more than half of South Africa's whites live.
   The key question in the black municipal elections is whether the
government can prevent disruptions by militants and persuade a
significant number of candidates to participate, despite the
likelihood that these will be depicted as apologists for the
government.
   Defense Minister Magnus Malan told Parliament last month that
``radicals and revolutionaries ... regard the elections as a prime
target for disruption and intimidation.''
   ``It is my duty and your duty to ensure that these elections are
a success,'' he told lawmakers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
