<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ToxicWaste     06-12 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toxic Waste,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Withdrawn From Toxic Waste Site For Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police guarding a site where European
toxic waste was secretly dumped withdrew after chemists confirmed
the material was poisonous, the News Agency of Nigeria said Sunday.
   Assistant police inspector Aminu Malumfashi said they left the
site in Bendel state for their own safety, the agency said. They
had sealed off the area to keep the public away.
   The military government announced Saturday that preliminary
tests of waste show the substances to be poisonous. Scientists
urged that all people who visited the area undergo medical tests.
   The waste, which included radioactive material, was dumped near
the town of Koko, 150 miles southeast of Lagos.
   The dumping episode, the latest in a series of alleged efforts
by European and American companies to dump hazardous waste in West
Africa, has strained relations between Nigeria and Italy.
   Nigeria has recalled its ambassador to Rome and demanded that an
Italian ship remove the waste, which had been imported by an
Italian company working for 10 European firms.
   Italy has said it is cooperating in an investigation.
   Norway, whose honorary consul general in Guinea was arrested for
complicity in the dumping of waste there, said the waste would be
returned to Norway.
   On May 31, five Congolese, including three senior government
officials, were charged with plotting to secretly import toxic
waste for dumping there.
</TEXT>
