<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-88 1610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WrightBook     06-12 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright Book,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friend Says He Paid $6,000 For Speaker's Books</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright Ethics Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A longtime friend of House Speaker Jim
Wright says he paid Wright $6,000 for copies of his books as a
legal way to get around federal limits on campaign contributions.
   Fort Worth developer S. Gene Payte, who has known Wright since
he entered Congress in 1955, told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram he
bought 1,000 copies of the book to ``show my appreciation.''
   Federal election laws limit individual campaign contributions to
$1,000 for each election.
   Payte said knew about the limit but wanted to find a way to
boost Wright's income, the Star-Telegram reported Sunday.
   ``If I wanted to help Jim and wanted to give him some money, I
couldn't do it,'' he said. ``But I could buy his books.''
   Payte also said he wrote letters to nearly 50 Fort Worth
businessmen urging them each to buy $1,000 worth of the books, but
did not know if they followed up on the request. He would not name
them.
   The House Ethics Committee decided last week to conduct a
inquiry to determine if Wright has violated rules on ethics and
conflicts of interest.
   One aspect of the inquiry will be the publication arrangements
for his 1984 book ``Reflections of a Public Man.''
   Fort Worth orthodontist Gene Wood, another longtime Wright
friend, said he paid $1,000 to publisher William Carlos Moore after
Moore told him he was trying to put together a group of about 20
people to finance republication of the book last year.
   ``I paid to have some republished and a big box (of books) was
sent to me,'' Wood said. He added that he had already given Wright
the maximum $1,000 in campaign contributions.
   Wright has acknowledged that some supporters bought large
numbers of books, but said it wasn't an attempt to get around
contribution limits.
   ``I think that's a mistake,'' Wright said. ``I don't think
anybody really thought that.''
   Wright instead said, ``I'm glad they thought enough of the
book.''
   Meanwhile, another longtime Fort Worth friend of Wright said he
was present when Wright asked a congressional aide if he would
``sacrifice a couple of weekends'' to work on the book.
   Ben Procter, professor of history at Texas Christian University,
located in Fort Worth, recalled the request in a sworn statement
Wright provided the ethics committee Friday.
   One charge the committee will investigate is whether Wright paid
the aide, Matthew Cossolotto, $2,000 in public money to help
compile the book.
   The House ethics manual says congressional employees may not be
paid from public funds to perform personal or campaign activities
on behalf of a congressman.
</TEXT>
