<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DecatursContest     06-12 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Decaturs Contest,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decaturs Of The World Compete To Raise Food For The Needy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials have learned the answer to
the question on their promotional T-shirts: ``Where the heck's
Decatur?''
   There's a Decatur almost everywhere, from Alaska to Mississippi
_ 28 at last count.
   And the smaller Decaturs have accepted the challenge of the
largest to collect food for the poor and put themselves on the map.
   Local organizers created ``Cans Across The Country'' to see
which Decatur could collect the most food and provide it to hungry
people in each of the communities. The goal is one can of food for
each resident _ a potential of about 200,000 cans.
   ``The real winners will be the recipients of the food,'' said
Ann Lewellen of The Decatur Advantage, an organization that
promotes the Illinois city of about 94,000 residents.
   ``But every Decatur that participates will be a winner because a
grass-roots movement with volunteers working for a common good
generates a spirit of unity. That makes a community stronger,'' she
said.
   Ms. Lewellen initially identified nine other cities of Decatur
and two Decatur counties, and Mayor Gary Anderson mailed a white
glove to each to begin the competition Memorial Day weekend.
   The official T-shirt of the contest has a United States map on
the front. The question mark in ``Where the heck's Decatur?'' rests
in Illinois.
   But, as word of the contest spread across the country, Illinois
officials realized their count of 12 Decaturs was short.
   ``This little town of Decatur in New York called,'' said Ms.
Lewellen. ``Decatur townships surfaced. There's even one in San
Juan County, Wash., population 20, except in the summer when it's
100. Many of them don't even have a zip code.''
   Her count rose to 25. The Decatur Herald & Review did some
additional research and identified 28 Decaturs.
   ``I'm not sure we're through finding Decaturs yet,'' said the
mayor. ``But, the more the merrier.''
   All are welcome in the contest, which has has been divided into
three divisions based on population. There are no prizes, said the
mayor, ``just satisfaction and pride.''
   Officials from all the Decaturs will be invited to the opening
ceremony of Decatur Celebration here Aug. 5. The winners will be
announced then, although some Decatur officials figure they have
victory wrapped up.
   ``There's no doubt in my mind,'' said Mayor Bobby Wilson of
Decatur, Texas. ``We've never been beaten at anything. I'll be
there to pick up my first-place trophy and to bring y'all some
chili and jalapeno peppers.''
   The mayor of Decatur, Ga., promised Anderson a consolation prize
of a pinto bean-and-peanut butter sandwich, and Mayor Bill Dukes of
Decatur, Ala., said schoolchildren brought 7,000 cans of food in
just one day, and ``we're going to beat Decatur, Ill.''
   Anderson said the contest will increase public awareness about
all of the Decaturs _ communities named for Commodore Stephen
Irving Decatur, a patriot and U.S. Navy hero in the War of 1812.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
