<HEAD>Thousands Of Counterfeit Watches Seized From Waikiki Vendors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seizure of nearly 5,100 counterfeit designer
watches from two dozen Waikiki vendors is the largest seizure of
its kind in U.S. history, a federal official said.
   U.S. marshals and state sheriff's deputies armed with a federal
warrant raided the shops Friday, said Jim Propotnick, chief deputy
U.S. marshal in Honolulu.
   ``We just hit the mother lode,'' said Propotnick. ``We ended up
making the largest seizure of this type _ wristwatches _ that has
been done.''
   The warrant was requested by watchmakers Rolex, Gucci and Piaget
and was issued secretly Thursday by visiting U.S. District Judge
Laughlin Waters.
   Bill Ellis, a private detective hired by the manufactuers, said
the watches' movements were made in Japan and assembled in Hong
Kong.
   A Rolex watch which normally sells for $11,500 was being sold in
counterfeit version in Waikiki for $70 to $300, or as low as $25
for wholesale orders, Ellis said.
