<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF-LearRecord     06-12 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-Lear Record,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businessman Sets Climb Record In Private Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILLSBORO, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman has set a world record for
the fastest takeoff and climb to 10,000 feet in a private aircraft.
   Dan Hanna took a 23-year-old Lear jet from ``ground zero'' at
Hillsboro Airport to 10,000 feet in one minute and 13 seconds,
knocking five seconds off the old climbing record.
   The flight Friday was witnessed by Moya Lear, widow of Bill
Lear, the airplane's creator. ``It's particularly neat that it was
done with a 23-year-old plane,'' she said. ``It's still the best
plane in the air.''
   Hanna, of Portland, had been scheduled to make the record
attempt Saturday morning, but decided to try it Friday evening
because he felt the heavier and cooler night air would give the
Lear 23 maximum thrust.
   Hank Beaird, who in October 1963 was the first pilot to test the
Lear 23, timed the flight as a representative of the Federation
Aeronautique Internationale.
