<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-88 1636EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     06-12 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Officer: Speedboat Raid Off Saudi Coast A ``Surprise''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-owned supertanker anchored off
Bahrain on Sunday after an Iranian gunboat attack that apparently
caught U.S. military officials in the Persian Gulf by surprise.
   The 258,979-ton Esso Demetia, which flies the British flag, was
about 45 miles off the Saudi Arabian coast when it was ambushed by
two or three armed speedboats just before dusk Saturday.
   Iranian attacks in that area are extremely rare and perhaps
unprecedented, said one U.S. official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The attack ignited several fires aboard the supertanker but
caused no casualties, said gulf-based shipping executives, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The nearest American warship, the guided missile frigate
Halyburton, was 45 miles away, and it would have taken it 1{ hours
to reach the stricken ship.
   A Navy spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. Brad Goforth, said that by the time
the 3,600-ton frigate met the tanker heading for ``humanitarian
assistance,'' the Esso Demetia was sailing toward Bahrain under its
own power, had the fires under control and did not request help.
   Goforth said U.S. officials would not speculate further on the
attack on the Arab side of the gulf, far from Iran and the
customary haunts of its Revolutionary Guard raiders.
   The supertanker was originally reported to be British-owned, but
Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit on Sunday said it was
U.S.-owned, but it didn't know the firm.
   Senior U.S. officers have said Iran appeared to be testing U.S.
forces following April 18 clashes in which six of Iran's naval
craft were sunk or disabled.
   A U.S. officer speaking on condition of anonymity said the
daylight raid on the Esso Demetia was ``a surprise, not something
anyone was really looking for.''
   ``It's probably supposed to prove they can hit a ship anywhere
they want to,'' he said.
   Available records show that there have been no ship attacks by
Iran in the waters immediately north of Bahrain and east of Saudia
Arabia for several years.
   Iraq and Iran have been fighting since 1980.
   The Esso Demetia attack was one of two raids on ships in four
hours Saturday.
   A Filipino crewman was killed and two others wounded in the
earlier raid on the 11,744-ton West German container ship
Dhaulagiri in the Strait of Hormuz, 350 miles to the southeast.
   Shipping executives said the raids were apparently in
retaliation for Iraqi air strikes on Iran's oil shipping. Iraq
claimed attacks Thursday and Friday but only the first was verified
independently.
   Under recently expanded ``rules of engagement,'' U.S. warships
may respond to requests for help from ships under attack in
international waters, regardless of what flag they fly. American
ships cannot help vessels carrying war-related or contraband cargo.
   Previously, U.S. warships could defend only U.S.-flagged vessels.
   Since the tougher policy went into effect May 3, Iran has
carried out six gunboat attacks, all far enough from patrolling
U.S. warships that they could not intervene.
   Baghdad's official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
quoted a military communique as saying Iraqi jets shot down an
Iranian F-14 Tomcat fighter over the gulf Saturday.
   But Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency denied that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
