<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CaptiveWomen     06-12 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Captive Women,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins Monday In Pittsburgh For Heidnik Murder
Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection was sscheduled to begin
Monday in Pittsburgh for the murder trial of a man charged with
torturing and raping six women, killing two of them, and whose
freezer contained human body parts.
   Gary Heidnik, who is white, is accused of keeping black women
chained in the basement of his row house where, survivors have
testified, he dug screwdrivers into their ears, raped them almost
every day and fed them dog food.
   Six jurors had been chosen in Philadelphia when Common Pleas
Judge Lynne M. Abraham agreed to a defense request to move jury
selection out of town. Those six jurors were dismissed. State Chief
Justice Robert N.C. Nix chose Allegheny County for jury selection;
those chosen will be sequestered for the trial in Philadelphia.
   The judge ordered the change of jury selection because Heidnik,
44, had his lawyer tell the court he didn't believe he would get a
fair shake from Philadelphians.
   Heidnik has a history of mistreating women, and was confined to
maximum-security mental hospital after a 1978 conviction for
kidnapping a retarded person he was charged with raping. Heidnik
told a judge he had been diagnosed as schizophrenic.
   Defense attorney A. Charles Peruto Jr. has said Heidnik, an Army
veteran with a psychiatric disability, was a subject of Army LSD
experiments in the mid-1960s that aggravated his schizophrenia. The
Army says there is nothing in Heidnik's records showing that, but
Peruto has said he has documents to back up his claim in court.
   Peruto and the prosecutor, Assistant District Attorney Charles
Gallagher, have been barred by a judge from making any public
comments on the case, at least until the jury is chosen.
   Heidnik, self-styled minister of a church he created and
operated in his home, also turned out to be a financial whiz,
turning $35,000 into a stock portfolio worth more than $500,000 in
10 years.
   Heidnik was arrested in March 1987 after a woman told police she
had escaped from him.
   Police said they found three other women, aged 18 to 24 and
naked from the waist down, chained in the basement, two to a pipe
and the other in a water-filled pit. When they were released they
ran into the street crying ``Free at last.''
   In a freezer were 24 pounds of human limbs with other body parts
in a kitchen refrigerator, police said. The woman who said she
escaped later led detectives to a remote forest area in southern
New Jersey, where they found the body of Debbi Johnson, 23.
   Authorities said Ms. Johnson was electrocuted while standing in
the water-filled pit when the defendant allegedly touched electric
wires to her chains.
   Heidnik also is accused of killing Sandra Lindsay, 24. She died
while hanging for days by one hand shackled to a basement pipe,
authorities said.
   District Attorney Ronald Castille said after Heidnik's arrest
that the reason it took so long to arrest him was that, despite
complaints from neighbors, police had no probable cause.
   ``We can't go walking into people's houses,'' said Police
Inspector James Gallagher. ``We can't just go kicking in doors and
running in.''
   In 1986 Heidnik's estranged wife obtained an order prohibiting
him from ``physically striking, harrassing or threatening'' her.
The document, filed in Family Court, said Heidnik regularly picked
up ``black handicapped women for the purpose of having sex with
them.''
   When neighbors complained in February 1987, a month before his
arrest, about a smell coming from his home Heidnik told police that
a pot of meat had burned.
   ``It's just amazing to me that this could have gone on as long
as it did in the city without someone picking it up,'' said Karen
Kulp, executive director of Women Organized Against Rape.
</TEXT>
