<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Roast     06-12 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Roast,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Takes Humorous Jabs At Bush And Himself At Press Roast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated ress Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis responded with a bit of
mimicry when he received a mock congratulatory telegram from
President Reagan and his wife, Nancy, at a press roast.
   ``Thank you, Dan,'' said the straight-faced recipient.
   Dan? Yes, Dan, as in CBS anchorman Dan Rather, who had an
infamous interview with Dukakis' Republican opponent, George Bush.
And ``Dan'' as in the name Bush repeatedly used to refer to his
interviewer, Ted Koppel, on ABC-TV's ``Nightline'' program last
week.
   It was a night of lampoons Saturday as Dukakis was honored by
the Boston Press Photographers Association. The Massachusetts
governor poked fun at his chief rival, selection of a running mate
and even himself.
   Dukakis told the gathering he took a break that afternoon to go
``to a Harvard boutique to pick up my speech for tomorrow,'' a
tounge-in-cheek jibe at Bush's characterization of Dukakis as an
elitist.
   He joked about picking a vice president, pointing a finger down
the head table at Steve Nelson, a former linebacker for the New
England Patriots football team.
   ``He knows something about defense and I'm interested in
conventional defense,'' Dukakis told his receptive _ and laughing _
audience. ``I've been thinking about Nelson.''
   The unusually festive Dukakis, who rarely tries to be funny,
accepted the barbs as well as dishing them out.
   Master of ceremonies Bob Warren presented him with a cardboard
presidential seal with a likeness of a cod in place of the bald
eagle.
   He laughed again when another seal was attached to the podium;
the sign said the official seal of ``The Next President of the
United States.''
   And he roared when Warren presented him with catalogs and a
shopping bag from one of Washington's pricier shops, telling
Dukakis they were for his wife, Kitty, whose penchant for finer
clothing contrasts sharply with her husband's love of
bargain-basement suits.
   ``We know you don't shop,'' said Warren.
   The host told Dukakis he had the Boston press to thank for
helping him develop ``that fine-tuned media style the rest of the
nation now finds so riveting and charasmatic.''
   For the sake of fairness, Warren noted Bush's attacks on
Dukakis' suburban upbringing and fired back:
   ``Kennebunkport isn't exactly tent city, you know,'' a reference
to the vice president's sprawling oceanside summer compound in
Maine.
</TEXT>
