<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MillionaireBartender     06-12 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Millionaire Bartender,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bartender Cashes In On $35 Million Lottery Jackpot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STONE PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debbie Buchanan was working her regular
shift as a bartender at the Snick-Snack Tap when her dream turned
to reality _ she won a piece of a $35 million lottery jackpot, the
second largest in state history.
   ``I was just sitting at the bar, comparing my tickets against
the number, when I said, `I got three, I got four, I got, five, I
got six,''' Ms. Buchanan, 28, said after the Saturday night Lotto
drawing.
   Earlier in the day, Ms. Buchanan had bought $10 worth of Lotto
tickets along with Tony Godinez, 23, her boyfriend's brother, in
this west Chicago suburb.
   Godinez, a laid-off construction worker and father of two, said
Sunday that it didn't take long for news of his good fortune to get
around.
   ``I've had a lot of phone calls. They say, `Hey, Tony, you
remember me from school, don't you?' I say, `No, goodbye.'''
   The ticket purchased by Ms. Buchanan and Godinez was one of
three winning tickets in the Lotto drawing, which had a guaranteed
grand prize for a single winner of $35 million, paid in the form of
an annuity over 20 years.
   Since the grand prize money will be divided among three winners,
officials won't know until Monday how large an annuity each third
of the jackpot will buy, said lottery spokeswoman Kathy Rem.
   They also won't be able to confirm the winners until Monday,
each of whom faced odds of 12.9 million-to-1 in picking the six
winning numbers, Ms. Rem said.
   The other winning tickets _ which matched the numbers 2, 4, 9,
31, 42 and 45 _ were bought in the south Chicago suburb of Steger
and in Rockford, she said.
   The $35 million Illinois jackpot is second only to the $40
million Lotto jackpot won by Mike Wittkowski on Sept. 1, 1984.
   Ms. Buchanan said Sunday she had not had time to think about
what she would do with her winnings, other than ``get my mom a
(new) house.'' The daughter is single, lives at home with her
mother and two brothers, and has worked at the Snick-Snack for
about two years.
   ``This bar is one big family. We all know each other, so when we
found out that me and Tony had won, it was like the whole family
had won,'' she said.
   ``I haven't been able to sit down and think about what I'm going
to do with the money,'' Godinez said.
   As for the reaction of his brother, Armando Godinez, whom Ms.
Buchanan has been seeing, Tony Godinez quipped, ``What else is he
going to say but, `Let's get married?' If he's smart, that's what
he'll say.''
   Kidding aside, Tony Godinez said he won't have to work any more
part-time construction jobs ``to put food on the table'' for his
wife and youngsters, Eric, 3, and Jacqueline, 16 months.
   ``We joke a little, we pray to God a little, and we thank him
for what he's given us,'' he said.
</TEXT>
