<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Over Northern Plains, Record Lows In South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms produced violent weather, but also brought
much-needed rain, over the drought-stricken northern Plains on
Sunday. There were record high temperatures in Michigan and record
lows in the South.
   Thunderstorms developed along a cold front and extended from
eastern North Dakota and northwestern Minnesota across central
South Dakota.
   Thunderstorms produced wind gusts to 60 mph at Mobridge, S.D.,
and gusts to 62 mph at Jamestown, N.D. High wind downed a tree and
damaged a roof at Tappen, N.D., the National Weather Service said.
   Mobridge got 1.47 inches of rain during the six hours up to 2
p.m. EDT and Jamestown got 0.80 of an inch.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms continued across extreme
southern Florida and isolated showers were over the rest of the
Gulf Coast. Miami got 1.62 inches of rain in the six hours up to 2
p.m.
   A few showers spread over the Northwest.
   Ahead of the cold front, highs were in the 80s and lower 90s
across much of the nation east of the Rockies. In northern
Michigan, Marquette hit a record 88 and Alpena hit a record 91.
   But the South had another day of record and record-tying lows,
including 40 at Asheville, N.C., tie; 39 at Batesville, Ark., tie;
45 at Bristol, Tenn.; 44 at Calico Rock, Ark.; 51 at Chattanooga,
Tenn., tie; 50 at El Dorado, Ark.; 53 at Huntsville, Ala.; 52 at
Jackson, Miss., tie; 47 at Knoxville, Tenn., tie; 48 at Mena, Ark.,
tie; 50 at Meridian, Miss.; 54 at Monroe, La.; 50 at Paducah, Ky.,
tie; 48 at Pinson, Ala., tie; and 53 at Shreveport, La.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at Helena, Mont., to 95 at Tucson, Ariz. The low for the
day was 30 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the northern and central Rockies to the northwestern half of
Minnesota, and across the southern half of Florida. Widely
scattered showers were forecast over northern Maine.
   Highs remaining below 80 were predicted from the coast of
Washington through Montana and Wyoming into western sections of the
Dakotas, including highs only in the 60s and upper 50s in Montana
and northwestern Wyoming; in the upper 70s in northern Maine; in
the 90s or above 100 in the valleys and deserts of the Southwest;
and mostly be in the 80s and low 90s elsewhere.
