<2ND_LINE>AM-Singleton,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Ax-Wielding Rapist Lists Florida Address, Records Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted rapist Lawrence Singleton, who
hacked off the arms of his teen-age victim, apparently has chosen
to settle in the Tampa area but may have violated a state law,
authorities say.
   Free after parole in California, Singleton was issued his
driver's license last week and listed a permanent address at a home
in northwest Hillsborough County, said sheriff's Col. Cal Henderson.
   ``I don't know anything about it,'' the home's owner told The
Tampa Tribune Sunday. The newspaper did not identify the homeowner
and officials do not know if he is related to Singleton.
   Local officials of the state Department of Highway Safety and
Motor Vehicles alerted the sheriff's office that Singleton received
a driver's license, Henderson said.
   Authorities say Singleton appears to have violated a state law
that requires felons to register with the local sheriff or the
state Department of Law Enforcement within 48 hours of arrival in a
county.
   Two detectives have been assigned to locate Singleton and cite
him for failing to register, Henderson said.
   Singleton, who was reared in Tampa, has been trailed by
controversy since his release from prison.
   Outraged Californians mounted campaigns when their communites
were mentioned as possible homes during his yearlong parole. He
spent weeks being shuttled among apartments and motels along the
California coast and wound up in a mobile home on the grounds of
San Quentin Prison until the parole expired.
   The 60-year-old former merchant seaman can travel as he pleases
after serving eight years of a 14-year sentence and the year's
probation.
   His parole ended in April and days later he came to Florida to
visit his sister's home.
   Singleton was convicted of raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker and
chopping her arms off. He left her for dead along a roadside in
1978, but she recovered and moved to a new home in the Pacific
Northwest.
</TEXT>
