<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-88 1939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Soviets     06-12 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Soviets,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genscher Welcomes Soviet Arms Reduction Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher welcomes a Soviet suggestion on a conventional arms treaty
with the West but only as a starting point for future negotiations,
Genscher's spokesman said Sunday.
   ``This will have to be looked at very closely, but it does show
a new thinking in the Soviet Union,'' spokesman Juergen Chrobog
told The Associated Press.
   He was referring to remarks by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze last week in New York indicating the Warsaw Pact
alliance was ready to make cuts in its conventional forces that
would not have to be matched equally by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   At a conference on East-West security Saturday in Potsdam, East
Germany, Genscher said he greeted the apparent change in the
Kremlin's position.
   ``This speech in New York (by Shevardnadze) is welcomed because
now it has been clearly stated that everywhere there is an (Warsaw
Pact) advantage, asymmetrical cuts will have to be made,'' Genscher
said at the three-day conference that ended Saturday.
   ``This is very important for us in view of the superiority by
the Eastern side in large-scale equipment (such as tanks),'' he
added.
   Earlier in the Potsdam conference, other Soviet officials said
the Warsaw Pact was ready to make asymmetrical cuts in its tank
force, but they linked such reductions with elimination of NATO's
advantages in fighter aircraft and attack helicopters.
   Chrobog said Genscher was pleased with the Soviet statements on
conventional arms ``but these are matters which we have to analyze
further'' along with West Germany's NATO allies.
   During the Potsdam conference the Soviet deputy foreign
minister, Ivan Aboymov, outlined the latest Soviet proposals
calling for a three-stage reduction of conventional forces in
Europe.
   He said the first stage would be an elimination of force
imbalances between NATO and the Warsaw Pact, followed by a
reduction of 500,000 troops on each side and then restructuring the
remaining forces to give them a defensive rather than offensive
capability.
</TEXT>
