<2ND_LINE>AM-Cave Accident,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Killed In Cave Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman trapped in the collapse of a cave
from which two male companions escaped was found dead early Sunday,
and a fire official said dry weather may have contributed to the
collapse.
   Crews using shovels and backhoes found the body of Virginia
Green, 23, of Hugo, in the rubble of the cave in a sandstone cliff
near the Mississippi River on the city's southeast side.
   Recent dry weather may have contributed to Saturday night's
accident in Battle Creek Park, said District Fire Chief Warren
Cook, referring to the fine, powdery rubble of disintegrated
sandstone.
   Mike Bryant, 21, of St. Paul, said the three were sitting in the
cave listening to a tape player when the accident occurred.
   ``I was in the mouth of the cave. Sand started coming, and I
heard rumbling and started running,'' Bryant said from St.
Paul-Ramsey Medical Center. ``Something hit me in the head. My legs
were completely buried under sand and rock.''
   He said Green was deeper in the cave but that he was not sure
why she didn't run out.
   Bryant suffered an ankle injury. Kevin Sederstrom, 22, of St.
Paul, said he escaped without injury.
</TEXT>
