<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SoCalQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0760 06-12 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SoCal Quake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0760,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede SAN BERNARDINO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Earthquake Shakes Inland Southern California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with Caltech measuring quake at 3.4. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ONTARIO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rolling earthquake shook this inland
area of Southern California on Sunday, but there were no immediate
reports of damage or injury, authorities said.
   The quake also was felt in the cities of San Bernardino, Fontana
and Riverside, about 50 miles east of Los Angeles.
   ``We thought someone had hit the building. We only got about two
or three calls on it,'' said dispatcher Teresa Paniagua at the
Fontana Police Department. None of the callers reported injuries or
damage, she said.
   The quake struck about 2:22 p.m. PDT, was centered about five
miles east-southeast of Ontario, and measured 3.4 on the Richter
scale, said Hall Daily, a spokesman for the California Institute of
Technology in Pasadena.
   The temblor was the second widely felt quake to hit Southern
California since Friday, when a shaker measuring 5.2 on the Richter
scale hit 40 miles northwest of Los Angeles and was felt in much of
central and southern California.
   Daily said initial data indicated it was unlikely the Sunday
quake was related to the one which struck Friday.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause
slight damage in the local area.
</TEXT>
