<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Premier,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Premier To Visit Moscow, Warsaw and Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Karoly Grosz said in an
interview broadcast Sunday he will visit Moscow early next month,
then go on to Warsaw and Washington.
   Grosz told Hungarian state television that for his trip to the
U.S. capital, ``I am having my first dinner jacket made, as I was
told it is customary to wear such on occasions there.''
   ``I don't know what I will do with it upon returning home,'' he
added.
   Visiting U.S. Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead told
newsmen at a briefing in the Foreign Ministry on June 8, ``We look
forward to welcoming him (Grosz) to the United States at the end of
July.''
   Grosz, who also is Hungarian Communist Party chief, said he will
visit Moscow at Mikhail Gorbachev's invitation and that his talks
with the Soviet leader will cover energy, raw material and
technology issues.
   Grosz made an indirect comment about a possible visit to
Romania, but gave no date or specifics and did not mention the
strained relations between the two Warsaw Pact allies and neighbors.
   Their relations have deteriorated with Hungary claiming that
Romania is depriving the 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians in Romania
of their ethnic and cultural rights. Romania has rejected the
accusations.
   Hungary also has also protested the planned elimination by the
year 2000 of more than 7,000 Romanian villages, including thousands
inhabited mainly by members of the Hungarian minority.
</TEXT>
