<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Children'sHome 1stLd_Writethru a0723 06-12 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home, 1st Ld _ Writethru, a0723,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Official Says Many Other Children Not In State Custody</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 15 graf to UPDATE with state welfare
commissioner's comments from afternoon news conference, Picks up
12th graf pvs. ``There have...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITFIELD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 60 children may have eluded
social workers who rounded up and removed residents of a boarding
home under investigation for abuse, the state Welfare Department
chief said Sunday.
   But state Welfare Commissioner Thomas Brittain said he was
unsure how many children may have been left behind when students
from the Bethel Home for Children near Lucedale were removed Friday
by the workers armed with a court order.
   ``There are still a whole lot of kids out there wandering around
somewhere that were released through a totally inappropriate
manner,'' Brittain said at a Sunday news conference.
   He said 66 children had been taken into custody, including a
runaway brought to a state mental institution, early Sunday morning.
   The children were rounded up near the campus of the 28-acre
home, at restaurants and along roadways.
   Even as welfare workers continued trying to reunite some of the
youngsters with their familes, the Rev. Herman Fountain, the home's
operator, said he was sheltering four or five youngsters who fled
the home before the workers arrived.
   ``I've still got a few soldiers left, and I'm trying to work
back to what it was before,'' said Fountain, 38, who established
the fundamentalist Christian home 10 years ago as what he calls a
last refuge for troubled kids.
   Fountain says he is a former heroin addict, and his experiences
on the streets of New York City qualify him to work with such
children.
   Fountain's comments drew a tight-lipped response from the judge
who ordered the Welfare Department to remove children from the home
that has come under criticism intermittently since 1980.
   ``I'll deal with it, but I'll deal with it Monday,'' Chancery
Judge Robert Oswald said in a telephone interview from his home.
   A court hearing is set for Monday morning in Lucedale to decide
where the children taken from Bethel will be placed.
   Brittain said ``between 10 and 15'' children already had been
released to their parents.
   The commissioner said he was satisfied with the state's handling
of the situation and was not worried that some parents might want
to sue the state for removing the children.
   Oswald ruled Friday that children at Bethel _ who range in age
from 10 to 17 and are mostly from outside Mississippi _ were
subjected ``to physical abuse, medical neglect and detention
amounting to imprisonment.'' He ordered their immediate removal.
   Brittain, who supervised the children's removal from the home,
said Saturday that medical examinations of some children showed
excessive use of corporal punishment.
   As for the children who have returned to Bethel since Friday,
Brittain said, ``We'll work with the court on that and follow the
court's direction on that.''
   There have been estimates that 120 to 160 children were at the
home.
   Fountain refused to provide the court a list with names and
addresses of the children and their parents.
   Fountain vowed Saturday in a telephone interview from Lucedale
to continue to keep open Bethel's doors and said he had taken in
another resident, a teen-age boy, despite the judge's Friday order.
   ``To tell you the truth, I don't know how that court order
reads,'' he said.
   Charges that he enslaved and beat children are half-truths,
Fountain said. The children were brought to him precisely because
they needed strong discipline and hard work to set them on a
spiritual path.
   ``The parents have lost control. Kids today are such
manipulators. Such cons. Especially a child from a divorce. They've
learned how to manipulate their parents,'' the independent Baptist
minister said.
   ``The children are here mainly for runaways, stealing,
homosexuality. We have little girls who were whores,'' he said.
``They need a little discipline, a little bit of hard work. We give
them the Bible, not that trash they read, not rock 'n' roll. They
are going to do work when they are here.''
   Fountain believes the state welfare department is in conspiracy
against him, a conspiracy that runs so deep, those involved are
unaware. The conspiracy is based on the principles of humanism, an
anathema to his own fundamentalist beliefs and his advocacy of
separation between church and state, he claims.
   The conspiracy's aim, he said, is to set up licensing laws for
church-run homes, something he insists he will never submit to.
</TEXT>
