<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0748 06-12 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0748,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Blasts Reagan On Drugs; Supports Use Of Military</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 2 to restore dropped word `apparent'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Michael Dukakis on
Sunday called President Reagan's anti-drug programs ``chaos'' and
promised the nation's mayors a tough program to curb drug use and
trafficking that would include the possible use of military force.
   The Massachusetts governor, who has enough delegates to secure
the Democratic presidential nomination, called for stronger drug
laws and stringent sentencing guidelines, but stopped short of
endorsing capital punishment for major dealers, which apparent
Republican nominee George Bush supports.
   ``My friends, we can win the war against drugs,'' Dukakis said
in a speech to the U.S. Conference of Mayors, where he picked up
endorsements from more than 500 Democratic mayors.
   ``But we have to recognize that it is war _ a war of wills, a
war of values, a war of confidence and courage and strength,'' he
said in his speech to the mayors.
   Dukakis also reiterated his pledge to raise taxes only as a last
resort, and told the mayors he welcomed their suggestions on
potential running mates. ``A lot of people are going to be
considered,'' he told reporters prior to the speech.
   Dukakis touted a Massachusetts program that brings drug
education to students and teachers and involves police and local
celebrities, promising to establish a similar national program if
elected.
   He said a national program should have the goal of ridding the
nation's schools of drugs by the 1990s and guaranteeing immediate
treatment for addicts.
   ``Now some may say that goal is too ambitious, that we'll never
make it,'' Dukakis said. ``But if we don't set ambitious goals for
our young people and for our nation, how are we ever going to win
this war?''
   In a scathing indictment of Reagan's anti-drug effort, Dukakis
said the president has failed to back up his tough rhetoric and has
undermined the war on drugs by cutting the Coast Guard budget, by
slashing federal aid to state and local police, by failing to
appoint a federal drug Czar, and by dealing with suspected drug
runners _ particularly Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``What we have today is chaos,'' Dukakis said. ``We've got to
back up what we say with what we do.''
   Dukakis promised the mayors to beef up federal law enforcement
staffs and to increase federal aid to state and local police,
although he did not suggest a specific dollar amount when asked by
reporters.
   He also said, ``We've got to move the war against narcotics from
the bottom to the top of our foreign policy agenda.''
   Dukakis said that if elected he would issue an executive order
prohibiting the payment of CIA or other government funds to
suspected drug dealers.
   ``Never again, never again are you going to bankroll a drug
peddler who is poisoning our society and killing are children,''
Dukakis said.
   He also said he would use increased amounts of U.S. foreign aid
for crop eradication and other drug interdiction efforts, including
the protection of politicians, police and judges in drug-producing
countries whose lives are threatened by drug kingpins.
   The military should be prepared to assist in such efforts, said
Dukakis, who again did not provide specific dollar figures on the
foreign aid proposal.
   ``It will take tough, sustained and unrelenting enforcement, on
the ground, in the air and at sea _ at home and abroad,'' Dukakis
said. ``Enforcement which uses the military where appropriate and
necessary.''
   He also chided Reagan for not working with Latin American
leaders to oust Noriega, saying such cooperation was vital to
stopping the flow of cocaine and marijuana into the United States.
   After his speech, Dukakis met with Democratic mayors and later
was holding a private session with a smaller group of black mayors.
   He was returning to Boston Sunday night and was to meet Monday
with congressional leaders and law enforcement officials from
several states to discuss drug issues.
</TEXT>
