<HEAD>Hooligans Abroad: Britain Tries To Salvage Its Overseas Image</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The image of the British traveler, once a model of
courtesy and reserve, has apparently been given a black eye by a
new breed of bad-mannered Britons.
   So the government, worried about its hooligans abroad, has
launched a television advertising campaign aimed at salvaging the
stiff-upper-lip image of its citizens overseas.
   ``It is a fact that over the years, particularly where the
British are going in vast numbers on holidays, there are
problems,'' a Foreign Office spokesman explained Sunday.
   Those problems include Britons who wind up in trouble with the
local law as well as crimes committed against British tourists.
   ``Those figures have gone up enormously,'' the spokesman said
anonymously, in keeping with British practice.
   British sports fans following their teams to games on the
Continent have run into serious trouble with police. Because of
violence at soccer games, British soccer clubs have been barred
from European Cup competition since 1985.
   The Foreign Office decided to launch the summer advertising
campaign in two weeks to back up its leaflet called ``Get It Right
Before You Go.''
   It will urge travelers to take out proper insurance and remind
them to abide by the laws of their host country during their stay.
   Foreign Office Minister Timothy Eggar goes to Spain this week to
inspect arrangements being made to handle the annual flood of
British tourists to the Mediterranean beach resorts.
