<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Protests     06-12 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Protests,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Government Protests in Gdansk and Warsaw</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 people rallied Sunday outside
the Gdansk apartment of Solidarity founder Lech Walesz and shouted
anti-government slogans.
   In Warsaw, police detained two men who were tossing leaflets and
demanding the release of jailed draft resisters, opposition
spokesman Marek Kosakowski reported.
   He said Gwido Zlatkes and Tomasz Gleb of the banned Freedom and
Peace organization climbed scaffolding on a main street near the
Royal Castle and threw some 1,500 leaflets to the crowd below.
   Kosakowski said many in the crowd, which he estimated to number
about 1,000, hooted and jeered police who tried to remove the two
from the scaffold.
   Zlatkes and Gleb climbed down about five minutes later and were
immediatelsy detained, according to Kosakowski.
   He said the leaflets listed 16 people as being imprisoned for
refusing mandatory military service, including Slawomir Dutkiewicz,
24. Freedom and Peace has said Dutkiewicz has been on a hunger
strike since being jailed seven months ago and is being force-fed
in prison.
   Walesa said in a telephone interview he was surprised by the
rally that developed after an outdoor Mass near his apartment in
the Baltic port city.
   The demonstrators marched to his apartment building shouting
``We want Lech, not Wojciech!'' and ``No freedom without
Solidarity!''
   Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski is the communist government's premier.
   Walesa said in the interview that he had not attended the Mass
and decided to address the crowd when many people shouted they
would boycott elections June 19 for municipal and provincial
councils.
   ``I said that the generals should know that was what people are
really thinking. I said that because we are not being noticed, we
should prepare ourselves for August in order to lead Poland into a
real road of reforms,'' Walesa said in the interview.
   Solidarity was chartered by the government as the first free
trade union in the Soviet bloc following nationwide strikes in
August 1981. It was suspended in December 1981 and subsequently
outlawed.
   Walesa joined in a strike May 2-10 at the Lenin shipyard in
Gdansk, where he works as an electrician.
   The strike ended without a settlement and Walesa said later that
unless authorities initiate a dialogue with Solidarity, Poland can
expect more strikes, probably in August.

</TEXT>
