<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IrishInsult 1stLd-Writethru a0735 06-12 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish Insult, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0735,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish-American Group Stages `Tee Party' To Protest Offensive
Article</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts two grafs after 6th graf ``The article quoted'' to
add information about the tone and content of the article. Picks up
7th graf ``The protesters.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crowd of about 40 people, most of them
Irish-American, tossed copies of Golf Digest into Boston Harbor on
Sunday in a ``Tee party'' to protest slurs against the Irish
contained in a Digest article.
   The demonstration against the article, ``The Role of the Irish
at The Country Club,'' took place about seven miles from The
Country Club, site of the 1988 U.S. Open golf championship this
week.
   The article, by British writer Peter Dobereiner, enraged
Irish-Americans, Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn and Cardinal Bernard
Law, among others, for its depiction of Irish as lazy drunkards.
   The furor was intensified when The Boston Sunday Globe reprinted
the piece as an advertising supplement in some 250,000 copies of
the paper. When the controversy erupted late last week, the
newspaper issued an apology but said it was too late to withdraw
the special inserts.
   In addition, The Globe printed an apology on Page 3 of the
Sunday paper, and Golf Digest apologized in an advertisment in the
Globe sports section. Last week, Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, president
of The New York Times Co., parent company of Golf Digest, sent
Flynn a written apology.
   The article quoted a fictitious member of the 106-year-old club
in the 1880s as saying, ``It's getting so you can't walk around
Boston without tripping over a drunken Kerryman. If we are to
preserve our way of life we must have somewhere to go on weekends .
.. with a high fence to keep the Irish out.''
   The article was apparently intended as humor and written
satirically from the perspective of a historical scholar. It
contained absurdities about the Irish role in building the country
club such as this:
   ``Of course they had to employ Irish laborers to do the heavy
work, but they employed an English construction superintendent who
contracted laryngitis from constantly shouting `Green side up!'
while the workers were sodding the golf course....''
   The protesters gathered Sunday on Castle Island, a peninsula off
the predominantly Irish-American neighborhood of South Boston, and
threw about 20 copies of Golf Digest into the harbor. They also
called for the United States Golf Association to ban Dobereiner
from the grounds of the Open.
   The magazines were later retrieved so as not to litter the
harbor.
   ``We have a right to expect that the Globe would not showcase an
article that was blatantly racist,'' said Kieran Staunton, Boston
editor of The Irish Voice, a weekly newspaper that first drew
attention to the article.
   Globe spokesman Richard Gulla said Sunday retrieving all copies
of the ad would have been impossible, because it was contained in a
section of the paper delivered a week in advance to retail stores
and distributors. Those sections are later sold along with the news
pages.
   An unspecified number of copies of the offending advertisement
were retrieved, he said.
   Only 250,000 of the Globe's 800,000 Sunday papers included the
article because Golf Digest wanted to reach a targeted audience,
Gulla said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
