<HEAD>Treasures From Four Shipwrecks Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold coins and uncorked bottles of
champagne were among the treasures from four shipwrecks, including
the Titanic's sister ship, sold at auction Sunday.
   Recovered items from the R.M.S. Republic, the Spanish galleon
Atocha, the ``Good Luck Wreck'' Regina and the Dutch trade ship
Geldermalsen were sold at the Museum of Yachting.
   About 500 people attended Sunday's auction to bid on such items
as the blue-and-white porcelain recovered from the Geldermalsen.
   Among the items from the Republic were cut glass decanters and
the helm wheel. The Titanic's sister ship, the Republic sank off
the coast of Nantucket, Mass., in 1909.
   On sale from the Regina were navigation lights and bottles of
champagne and scotch.
   About 300 bottles of liquor were brought up from the boat in
salvage operations last fall before cold weather halted the
operation. Workers said several thousand bottles remain underwater.
   The ship was dubbed the ``Good Luck Wreck'' because of the large
number of horseshoes found on board.
