<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-88 2133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Presbyterians 1stLd-Writethru a0700 06-12 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presbyterians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,0616</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs on subcommittee action Sunday night,
picks up 9th graf pvs ``A nominating ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed major Presbyterian statement on
nuclear war was revised Sunday to say a Christian ``normally''
should support the government and nuclear deterrence is immoral
``as an end in inself.''
   A writing team working over the weekend on ``Christian Obedience
in a Nuclear Age'' made the changes, which a subcommittee then
adopted.
   The changes will be presented to a full committee Monday, and
the 200th General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) is
scheduled to take up the paper Tuesday.
   Also on the agenda when 630 delegates of the nation's largest
Presbyterian body return to work Monday are the election of a top
denominational officer and a host of other issues, including
pornography, Israel's treatment of Palestinians in occupied
territories and religious freedom.
   The subcommittee of 18 people, including lay, clergy, youth and
seminary advisory delegates, generally adopted the work of the
writing committee Sunday.
   The writing panel had been charged with making the paper's
policy statement and background agree with the revised
recommendations made by the subcommittee earlier.
   Those changes included removing language that would strengthen
corporate church support for tax resisters and other government
protesters and soften language declaring nuclear deterrence immoral.
   The changes shifted some words to play down discussion of tax
resistance and added language saying Christian obedience to civil
authority ``is normally the case.''
   A paragraph was also added recognizing military service as a
legitimate Christian response.
   The revised policy statement also retains condemnation of
nuclear war as immoral. But the original declaration of nuclear
deterrence as being immoral was altered to add the phrase ``as an
end in itself.''
   The proposed policy statement now says: ``The policy of nuclear
deterrence has been in danger of becoming an end in itself rather
than an interim measure of self-defense. Such a policy as an end in
itself is not morally defensible. The work for peaceful
alternatives needs to be vigorously pursued.''
   Supporters of the initial paper said they expect the full
assembly Committee on Peacemaking and International Relations to
restore some of the original language.
   While opponents of the paper agreed that was possible,
``whatever they do to the document, it needs to be sent for
prayerful consideration'' by the church instead of adopted as a
policy, said John Boone, president of Presbyterians for Democracy
and Religious Freedom.
   A nominating committee's decision not to include an incumbent as
a candidate for a top denominational office caught the assembly by
surprise Saturday afternoon. There were indications commissioners
would face a contested election when they vote Tuesday.
   The Rev. James E. Andrews, 60, has been stated clerk or interim
co-stated clerk of the denomination since it was formed in 1983 by
the reunion of the Northern and Southern branches of the
Presbyterian church. Previously, he held the same office in the
Presbyterian Church (U.S), the Southern church, for 10 years.
   The committee nominated Harriet Nelson, a popular former
moderator _ or chief spokesman _ for the $62,000-a-year job.
   Andrews has said his name will be placed in nomination from the
assembly floor when voting begins. In addition, the Rev. Charles E.
Hurst, a local church executive from Pompano Beach, Fla., will be
nominated from the floor.
   Other committee recommendations include a call for Israel to end
its 20-year occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, with the
United States asked to stop sending aid which is used to subsidize
Israeli settlement of the territories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
