<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ZooAtlanta 1stLd-Writethru a0721 06-12 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zoo Atlanta, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0721,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Visit New `Rain Forest'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 7th graf ``Zoo Business'' with 2 grafs to CORRECT
Saturday attendance figures and add Sunday figures. Picks up 8th
graf pvs ``The four-acre...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie B. and the other gorillas in a new ``rain
forest'' at Zoo Atlanta seemed to take it in stride when the
general public was admitted to the attraction for the first time.
   Thousands of people streamed into the Ford African Rain Forest
after a ribbon-cutting ceremony Saturday to strain for a look at
Willie B., the zoo's biggest star, in the lush open-air habitat
which replaced the cage he occupied for 27 years.
   The 450-pound gorilla, now about 30 years old, immediately came
to the edge of a restraining moat to strut for the crowd; once, he
ran down a grassy slope, drawing applause.
   On each side, across moats, two families of gorillas recently
brought to the zoo kept a greater distance from onlookers but
remained mostly in the open and not in their shelters.
   Zoo Director Terry Maple said the gorillas, while physically
separated, have interacted in the 2{ weeks they have been together.
   ``They're vocalizing, they're beating their chests, they're
moving this way and influencing the others,'' Maple said. ``The
behavior of animals is enhanced by the presence of others.''
   Zoo Business Manager Dennis Baker said a record for paid
attendance at the zoo was set Saturday, and broken Sunday. Sunday's
crowd was 11,860, with 10,893 paid, passing the mark of 8,522 set
Saturday, when there were also nearly 5,000 free admissions.
   The zoo's best attendance was 17,000 in 1986 when there was free
admission to celebrate Willie B.'s birthday, but the record paid
attendance before Saturday was about 7,400, Baker said.
   The four-acre, $4.5 million rain forest, boosted by $1 million
donated by the Ford Motor Co., is the centerpiece of a renovation
of the 99-year-old zoo, dubbed one of the 10 worst in the country
by the U.S. Humane Society only four years ago.
   Three gorilla families, including the two already present, are
being provided by the Yerkes Regional Primate Research Center at
Atlanta's Emory University.
   The exhibit includes an adjacent aviary, featuring birds from
the same areas of West Africa inhabited by the gorillas.
   It is the second of 10 habitats planned; a flamingo habitat
opened first. Next year, Maple said, the zoo will present an east
African savanna, featuring lions and elephants and including a pool
deep enough for an elephant to immerse itself.
</TEXT>
