<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovak-Church     06-12 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovak-Church,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Demand More Roman Catholic priests in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRNAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 15,000 people packed inside
and around a church applauded Vatican demands Sunday that the
communist government permit more Roman Catholic bishops and priests.
   In the first ceremony of its kind since 1973, Vatican
representative Archbishop Francesco Colasuonno consecrated Jan
Sokol as a bishop and apostolic administrator of the archdiocese of
Trnava. The archdiocese is known as the ``Rome of Slovakia''
because of its many historic churches.
   In a 20-minute sermon interrupted at least two dozen times by
applause, Colasuonno called for bishops to fill the vacancies in
nine of the nation's 13 dioceses and more religious education.
   ``Religious life must regain its full rights in a secular
society,'' he said. ``Only if it has its rightful place can it
contribute to the progress and welfare of the citizens.''
   The Vatican emissary indicated Pope John Paul II wants much more
than the authorities' approval of the appointment of Sokol and of
two assistant bishops who were consecrated in Prague on Saturday.
   ``We hope that the negotiatons of the Holy See with all bodies .
.. will bring further results,'' said Colasuonno, speaking in
Slovak. Negotiations between the Vatican and government are
continuing.
   ``This work ... should not end with the appointment of bishops,
but should go much further,'' he said.
   After his consecration the 54-year-old Sokol said, ``I am sure
that this was the first step and that others will follow. The
vacant bishops' sees will soon be filled with good bishops
according to Jesus' heart.''
   There was light applause as the government representatives
entered the church for the ceremony. They sat unsmiling as
Colasuonno expressed the church's demands for more rights.
   ``Believers have the right to have well-prepared and educated
priests'' and orders of nuns and monks need more freedom to recruit
new members, the archbishop said.
   Czechoslovakia's Catholic primate, 88-year-old Cardinal
Frantisek Tomasek, has taken a tougher stand with communist
authorities in recent months.
   In January, he gave unprecedented backing to a petition
demanding religious freedom. Copies of the petitions have been
signed by an estimated 600,000 people in this country with a
population of 15.5 million.
   Tomasek presided at the consecration of the two assistant
bishops for his Prague archdiocese at Saturday's ceremony.
   After the ceremony several hundred people gathered outside
Tomasek's and chanted demands for more religious freedom.
   In Trnava, about 4,000 people were crowded into the church for
the ceremony Sunday and at least 11,000 gathered outside and
listened to the service carried by loudspeakers.
   Sokol was consecrated as a full bishop. But for the archdiocese
that is normally headed by an archbihop he officially serves as an
apostolic administrator.
</TEXT>
