<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ElderlyCenterFire     06-12 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elderly Center Fire,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Guts Retirement Apartment Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire gutted a residential apartment
complex for senior citizens Sunday in this southeastern Minnesota
town, but authorities searching the smoldering ruins believed
everyone was safe.
   Hastings Fire Chief Donald Latch said authorities believed all
residents of Oak Ridge Manor were accounted for. Firefighters
entered the burned-out three-story wood structure by midafternoon,
checking each room to see if anyone had been trapped.
   All residents, including some in wheelchairs, were believed to
have escaped, Latch said. ``If that's true, that's amazing,'' he
said.
   The fire's cause remained unknown, Latch said.
   The building had 106 units with 109 residents, said Jackie
Northard of the Red Cross disaster services team. About 40 to 50
people were evacuated from the building, the Dakota County
sheriff's office said.
   Mayor Lu Ann Stoffel said two or three buses took residents to
the hospital and a nursing home.
   Once they arrived, they were given lunch and offered medical
examinations, said Leslie Daley, a 75-year-old retired minister who
escaped the blaze.
   Since many residents had left with relatives for the weekend, it
was unknown how many were in the building when the blaze started.
   The Red Cross was providing food, clothing and housing, and
people volunteered their homes to the elderly residents, the mayor
said.
</TEXT>
