<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines 2ndLd-Writethru a0647 06-12 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0647,0844</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Foils Attempt By Pro-Marcos Group to Free Prisoners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT style. Pickup 3rd graf pvs
``Dulay has...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former soldiers loyal to deposed
President Ferdinand Marcos raided a military armory in a failed
attempt to free colleagues jailed for past coup attempts, the
military said.
   Maj. Gen. Ramon Montano, chief of the Philippine Constabulary,
said the group got away with 24 automatic rifles in their Saturday
attack. Montano said they had intended to free Orlando Dulay, a
former army colonel, provincial governor and assemblyman who was
close to Marcos when he was president.
   Dulay has been jailed at suburban Camp Crame for more than a
year on charges he ordered the killing of several supporters of
President Corazon Aquino during the 1986 presidential election that
ended Marcos' 20-year reign.
   The military also announced that it filed murder and kidnapping
charges against a Swede, a West German and a Filipino of German
descent who were arrested in a rebel-infested area on Wednesday.
   They were accused of taking part in a raid by communist New
People's Army guerrillas on a town southeast of Manila in February.
Two people were killed and two soldiers were abducted in the raid.
   Also Saturday, a Swiss judge ruled that assets held by Marcos in
Switzerland must be returned to his homeland. No figures were
given, but the assets involved were believed to be a small part of
the $1 billion that Philippine officials believe Marcos channeled
into Swiss bank accounts before he fled to exile in Hawaii.
   Marcos, who was living in Honolulu, said Saturday that he was
leaving the possibility of an appeal to his lawyers.
   The raid occurred at Camp Crame, the constabulary's national
headquarters. Most of the 160 detainees there are soldiers accused
of common crimes, but at least 34 of them are accused of taking
part in coup attempts against Mrs. Aquino.
   Montano said troops were prepared for the raid because of
intelligence reports earlier that ``Marcos loyalists'' would try to
free Dulay. He did not elaborate.
   He said the raiders broke into one office of the armory and
stole some weapons, then sped toward the jail compound in a van and
a car but were fired on by sentries who spotted them.
   The raiders immediately withdrew and were engaged in a brief
gunfight by other soldiers near the camp's gym, Montano said.
   Lt. Col. Cris Maralit, a constabulary spokesman, said some of
the raiders were believed hit in the exchange, but no casualty
figures given.
   A few hours later, troops were placed on maximum alert
nationwide, but officials said the move was not related to the Camp
Crame incident.
   They said the alert was a routine measure to prevent disruption
of Sunday's celebration of the 90th anniversary of the declaration
of Philippine independence from Spain.
   Late Saturday, the army chief of staff, Gen. Renato de Villa,
described the Camp Crame incident as an isolated one meant to
embarrass the government two days before Mrs. Aquino departs for
visits to Switzerland and Italy.
   ``We would like to appeal to our people not to be disturbed by
what happened at Camp Crame,'' he told reporters. ``I am very
confident that our commanders who are tasked ... to protect public
safety will be able to do their job.''
   Brig. Gen. Alejandro Galido, chief of the military's Southern
Luzon Command, said in a telephone interview that murder and
kidnapping charges against two Europeans and a Filipino were filed
Friday before a civil court in Quezon province.
   He claimed his command had ``heavy evidence'' against the Rev.
Klaus Schmidt, 52, a West German Protestant minister; Stellan
Hermansson, 30, a Swede who says he is a free-lance journalist; and
Antonio Bosch, a Filipino businessman.
   Sweden's Young Communist League said Friday in Stockholm that
Hermansson was the organization's president. It said he arrived in
the Philippines on May 18 to gather information for lectures and
was to have returned to Sweden Saturday.
   Hermansson and the two others were being held at the command
headquarters in Lucena, 60 miles southeast of Manila.
   Col. Hernani Figueroa said the charges stem from a New People's
Army raid on the Quezon province town of San Francisco last
February in which two police officers were killed and two soldiers
abducted.
   The soldiers, who eventually escaped, identified Schmidt,
Hermansson and Bosch as being with the San Francisco raiders,
Figueroa said.
   Hermansson denied the charges, said Eha Arg, first secretary of
the Swedish embassy. He visited Hermansson on Saturday.
   ``He (Hermansson) denies the charges, because he was not in the
country in February,'' Ms. Arg said in a telephone interview.
   A West German embassy officer visited Schmidt but could not be
contacted for comment because the mission was closed on the weekend.
   The military has accused the three of helping train communist
guerrillas.
</TEXT>
