<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Independence     06-12 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Independence,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Aquino Calls For Nationalism In Independence Day Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino proclaimed a
decade of nationalism Sunday and urged Filipinos to be steadfast in
the struggle against ``forces at home and abroad'' who want to keep
the country poor and subservient.
   Mrs. Aquino made the remarks from a grandstand at the seaside
Rizal Park as she led the country in the observance of the 90th
anniversary of the declaration by Filipino revolutionaries of
independence from Spain.
   About 20,000 people stood under a light drizzle and cloudy skies
during the ceremonies, which included a two-hour parade.
   Less than a mile away, hundreds of riot police blocked about
4,000 leftists who tried to march to the U.S. Embassy. The
protesters burned an American flag, chanted anti-U.S. slogans and
demanded the closure of U.S. military bases in the country.
   Still farther away on a downtown Manila square about 5,000
supporters of deposed President Ferdinand Marcos held a peaceful
rally during which they attacked Mrs. Aquino's government and
demanded the return of their exiled leader.
   In the liberty town of Angeles, 50 miles north of Manila, about
3,000 leftist protesters rallied outside the main gate of the U.S.
Clark Air Base. Police said the three-hour demonstration ended
peacefully.
</TEXT>
