<1ST_LINE>u i AM-US-CanadaTrade     06-12 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Canada Trade,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadians Stage Nationwide Protests Over U.S.-Canada Trade Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Canadians nationwide protested the
U.S.-Canada trade bill on Sunday by lighting candles, parading in
cars and stuffing phony ballot boxes with mock votes against the
agreement.
   Several groups of demonstrators in Ontario also rallied near
bridges and other border crossings at Niagara Falls, N.Y., Sault
Ste. Marie, Mich., and Duluth, Minn.
   Opponents of the Free Trade Agreement, which is to begin
relaxing trade barriers between the nations on Jan. 1, demanded
that Prime Minister Brian Mulroney call new elections for
Parliament before the bill goes into effect.
   ``We want a vote _ now,'' demonstrators chanted on Parliament
Hill in Ottawa.
   Trade bill opponents also shouted ``Lyin' Brian,'' a reference
to Mulroney's 1983 statements opposing free trade between the
nations.
   Protesters stuffed carboard boxes with mock ballots rejecting
what they called ``the sell-out of Canada.'' Elswhere,
demonstrators sang protest songs, paraded in cars and lit candles.
   Protests were reported in Edmonton, Alberta; St. John's,
Newfoundland; Victoria, Quebec; and numerous cities in Ontario.
   The protests Sunday were orchestrated by a coalition called the
Pro-Canada Network, a coalition of labor, social, women's, farm and
other groups. They say the bill will sell out Canada's economy,
culture and social programs.
   Mulroney and President Reagan signed the agreement Jan. 2. It
would eliminate tariffs and reduce other barriers in nearly every
facet of the $150 billion annual trading partnership.
   The changes would begin next year and be phased in during a
10-year period.
   The agreement, however, must be approved by Congress and
Parliament, and it faces staunch opposition from lawmakers in both
Washington and Ottawa.
   Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party controls 208 seats in
the 282-member House of Commons, but public opinion polls show
Canadians are sharply split on the agreement.
   Opposition stems from a variety of areas. Ontario grape growers,
for example, are upset because the agreement would eliminate an
automatic 65 percent markup on U.S.-made wine.
   Ontario, the industrial and financial giant of Canada's 10
provinces, has also seen strong opposition to the agreement.
   Liberal Lloyd Axworthy and New Democrat Steven Langdon both told
the Ottawa crowd Sunday they will continue attempts to block the
government's legislation in the Commons, where the bill is up for
second reading.
   ``We will make sure that Canadians get a full opportunity be
heard,'' said Axworthy.
   In Edmonton, Alberta, about 100 protestors gathered at city hall
and others picketed the homes of conservative ministers of
Parliament.
</TEXT>
