<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mexico-Autos     06-12 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Autos,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Urges Mexico to Encourage Ties with U.S. Auto Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study commissioned by the Mexican government
says Mexico should strengthen its ties to the U.S. automobile
industry by making it easier to export cars assembled in Mexico and
by upgrading its auto parts industry, according to a report
published Sunday.
   The Detroit News, which obtained the study, said it notes that a
closer alliance between the two nations' auto industries might
develop only if Mexico distinguished itself from Japan, South Korea
and other nations competing in the market.
   The study, conducted by the consulting firm Booz-Allen &
Hamilton Inc., was commissioned last year by the Mexican government
and the Bank of Mexico as part of efforts to obtain World Bank
loans for industrial restructuring.
   ``The Mexican government must differentiate Mexico from other
countries (Brazil, Taiwan, Korea and Japan) in the eyes of the U.S.
Congress and the U.S. public stressing proximity, cultural ties,
common problems and the long period of constructive
relationships,'' the study said.
   ``If U.S. protectionism grows and Mexico is lumped together with
Japan and Korea in retaliatory U.S. trade legislation, all of the
recommendations in this report are moot,'' it said.
   The study estimated that salaried auto workers in Mexico are
paid 20 percent to 25 percent of what their U.S. counterparts
receive.
   The study argued that the lower costs were part of ``Mexican
economic advantages within a North American auto production system
(that) saves jobs for U.S. workers.''
   ``Without access to Mexico, to selectively provide low-cost
labor as part of the overall process, more vehicles ... and parts
would be obtained from Brazil and various Far East countries with
the consequent loss of both U.S. and Mexican jobs,'' the study said.
   Booz-Allen recommended that Mexico immediately upgrade its auto
parts-making industy, which accounted for more than half of that
nation's $900 million auto exports trade surplus in 1986.
   The study also called for easing regulations on companies
already assembling cars in Mexico to encourage more exports to the
U.S. It also recommended that Mexico establish a technical center
in Detroit to keep pace with technological developments.
   The Big Three U.S. automakers each have assembly, engine and
parts plants in Mexico. Chrysler Corp. and General Motors Corp.
spokesmen said they were unaware of plans to increase investments
there. A Ford Motor Co. spokesman said company doesn't discuss
possible investments.
   Booz-Allen said Mexico would have to convince the United Auto
Workers union that an automotive alliance would benefit both
countries.
   But UAW Secretary-Treasurer Bill Casstevens said the union
remained opposed to Mexican auto investments that he said exploited
workers there and caused the loss of U.S. jobs.
   ``If the Mexicans develop a more competitive industry, it will
mean the loss of more jobs,'' he told the News.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880612-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-88 1859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Futures     06-12 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Futures,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Breed of Farmers Dealing Directly with Commodities Exchanges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMPSHIRE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The successful farmer of the future may
be the one who pays the closest attention to the futures, say a new
breed of computerized farmers who deal directly with the nation's
commodities exchanges.
   Clyde Hagemann, 44, who grows soybeans and corn and fattens
feeder cattle on his family's 1,800-acre farm near this Kane County
community, is typical of the new breed.
   Although Hagemann wears a soiled cap from a fertilizer company,
he doesn't resort to the marketing strategies many other farmers in
his area still use. Instead of delivering his corn and beans to the
local elevator every year and selling them through a forward
contract, Hagemann sells his crops and cattle months in advance in
complex contracts directly on the Chicago Board of Trade and the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Hagemann's computer and his constant electronic display of
commodity price quotes are as important to his farming as his
combine and his corn dryer.
   Experts say that by using the futures exchanges to market their
products, farmers can obtain price stability _ particularly in
volatile markets like the one being driven by the current drought _
along with marketing versatility, and they can maximize profits.
   Hagemann told the Chicago Tribune recently that he has been
dealing directly with the exchanges for 20 years, which makes him
something of a pioneer in the process, used by only 10 to 15
percent of the nation's farmers.
   Farm experts, commodities brokers and farm economy consultants
say farmers who learn the new marketing techniques have a definite
advantage over their more tradition-bound neighbors.
   ``The family farm is romantic history,'' says consultant Dan
Markey, who conducts marketing seminars for farmers throughout the
nation. ``Farmers must use modern business tools if they are to
survive, and that specifically includes the use of futures and
options.''
   Another farmer who hedges by selling and buying futures and
options contracts is Robert B. Johnson, 44, who operates a
3,000-acre corn, soybean and hog farm east of De Kalb. Johnson, who
studied the marketing techniques at a local junior college, says he
doesn't understand the attitude of other farmers who staged
demonstrations outside the Board of Trade some years back to
protest what they believed was price manipulation.
   ``The speculator does not set the price of the commodity; rather
the market sets the price,'' says Johnson.
   Nonetheless, Johnson and others advise them to make a serious
study of marketing techniques before attempting to use them.
   ``You cannot get too close to the market; particularly during
these times of extreme price volatility,'' warns computerized
Shabbona farmer Rob Mullins, 23. ``A lot of farmers come in here
and just watch the quotes as they come across the screen, when they
should be out watching their crops.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
