<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stock Prices Rise Moderately</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped with later prices on general news wires only.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved higher in early trading against
the Japanese yen Monday, while stock prices rose moderately.
   The dollar opened at 125.07 yen, up 0.22 yen from last Friday's
close of 124.85 yen.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said the
dollar was strengthened following a weekend remark by U.S. Federal
Reserve Board Vice Chairman Manuel Johnson that there was room for
the U.S. currency to rise.
   Johnson, speaking to reporters last Saturday in West Germany,
said he thought ``there would be a certain tolerance for (the
dollar to rise).''
   The dealer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the dollar
showed ``no major movements'' in early Tokyo trading because of
market holidays in Hong Kong and Sydney.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 151.66 points Friday, gained 59.59
points or 0.21 percent, in the first 15 minutes of trading, moving
to 27,979.95.
