<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Texaco-Icahn     06-12 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco, Icahn Face Showdown Later This Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Monday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. and its biggest shareholder, Carl C.
Icahn, may be headed for a showdown this week that could determine
the course of their acrimonious takeover dispute.
   Icahn is waging a proxy fight for five seats on the 14-member
Texaco board in an effort to pressure the oil giant to let
shareholders vote on his $60-a-share offer for the 85.2 percent of
Texaco stock that he does not already own.
   The bid values the entire company at $14.6 billion.
   The deadline for the proxy votes on the board seats is Friday
when Texaco plans to hold its annual shareholders meeting in Tulsa,
Okla.
   Texaco, which is based in White Plains, N.Y., has rejected
Icahn's buyout proposal, and has questioned his ability to finance
it.
   Wall Street has also been skeptical about the offer. Texaco
finished last week at $51.87{ a share on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   But Icahn has said he is so certain he could arrange the
financing that he says he would put $300 million in escrow for
payment to shareholders if he failed to arrange it by the date of
the shareholder vote on the offer.
   Meanwhile, a published report over the weekend said court
documents show an investment firm that has a large stake in Texaco
considered selling its stake and Icahn once tried to bring in
Canadian investor Marc Belzberg to buy it.
   The New York Times reported that the court papers indicate the
deal never took place, however, because the parties could not agree
on a price.
   The Times said its report on Saturday was based on documents
unsealed at the newspaper's request by Judge Gerard L. Goettel of
U.S. District Court in White Plains, who had earlier denied access
to depositions taken in suits between Icahn and Texaco related to
Icahn's takeover effort.
   The Times story said that Alan C. Greenberg, the chairman of
Bears, Stearns & Co., a brokerage house that bought stock for the
investment firm Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Co., said in a
deposition that Icahn once considered selling his shares to the
buyout firm.
   The newspaper said Greenberg was acting as a go-between, and in
several proposed transactions, the buyer and seller were unaware of
each other's identities.
   It said Greenberg did not identify Belzberg in his deposition,
but that a Bears Stearns lawyer did later. It said the deposition
makes clear that Icahn and not Greenberg recruited Belzberg as a
potential buyer.
   The newspaper said Greenberg's deposition indicates the
transaction never took place because the parties could not agree on
a price.
   On Friday, Icahn said he was forming a new holding company to
act as his sole vehicle for acquisitions, including a possible
hostile takeover bid for Texaco. He said the holding company
intended to raise up to $3.25 billion through an offering of stock
and debt securities.
   The Icahn group of companies also will contribute equity to the
holding company, including its 36.1 million shares of Texaco and
its interests in Trans World Airlines Inc. and ACF, a leasing
company.
   Icahn stated that if his slate was elected but a majority of the
Texaco board refused to allow a shareholder vote on the offer, he
would consider making a hostile bid for it through the new holding
company at yet to be determined terms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
